<BLOCK1><TI><UNDER>APPLICATION</UNDER></TI>
<P>1. The Applicants, Drew Keith Allen (&ldquo;Allen&rdquo;) and Susan Michelle Byrne (&ldquo;Byrne&rdquo;) make an application for:
<P1>a. An Order permitting removal of the boundary tree located between the property municipally known as [[location omitted] and [location omitted] [location omitted]and more fully described on Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>b. Damages in the amount of $5,000.00</P1>
<P1>c. The costs of this application including HST thereon; and</P1>
<P1>d. Such further and other relief as this Honourable Court may deem just.</P1></P>
<P>2. The grounds for the application are:
<P1>a. Allen and Byrne are the owners of the property located at [location omitted]</P1>
<P1>b. The Respondents, Meghan Ann MacDougall (&ldquo;MacDougall&rdquo;) and Nigel Hamid Scott (&ldquo;Scott&rdquo;) are the owners of the property located at[location omitted]</P1>
<P1>c. On [location omitted]there is a mature tree that started growing on[location omitted] but has now grown large it enough that a small percentage is now growing on [location omitted] (the &ldquo;Tree&rdquo;) that is the subject of this application.</P1>
<P1>d. Allen and Byrne wish to fully use and enjoy [location omitted]by building an addition and conducting renovations to the house situated on the property to provide more room for their family of 5, address significant heating and cooling issues, and deal with periodic flooding of the basement.</P1>
<P1>e. To that end, in April of 2017 Allen and Byrne retained the architectural firm of Spragge &amp; Company Architects Ltd. to prepare plans for an addition and renovation to the house.</P1>
<P1>f. As the Tree is in very close proximity to the current foundation wall of the house, which is intended to be moved under the proposed renovation plans, the design for the addition and renovation calls for the removal of the Tree. If the Tree is not removed then no addition to the house can be done.</P1>
<P1>g. Allen and Byrne applied to the City of Toronto on June 7, 2017 for building permits in order to implement the plans for the addition and renovation.</P1>
<P1>h. In order to implement the design of the addition and renovation, Allen and Byrne made an application to the Committee of Adjustments in August 2017 to consider approval of minor variances required by the proposed plans. As part of such application, Allen and Byrne obtained consents from 7 neighbouring property owners demonstrating support for the project, including their immediately adjacent neigbours to the South and to the West (apart from those at [location omitted]).</P1>
<P1>i. Allen met with Respondents in mid-December to advise them of the Applicants' intentions with their proposed renovation and that, regrettably, the renovation plan would not be possible to be carried out without seriously impacting the Tree and that Applicants expected it would be most likely necessary to remove the Tree.</P1>
<P1>j. MacDougall and Scott responded to the Applicants shortly after the meeting by email claiming that they considered the Tree a boundary tree, their right to consent was therefore required in order for Applicants to be able to remove the Tree, such consent was being withheld, and that this was unnegotiable.</P1>
<P1>k. MacDougall and Scott made written submission to the Committee of Adjustments by email on January 1, 2018 indicating that, while they did not oppose the planned renovation itself, they wished to voice their claim that the Tree was jointly owned by them and that they would not consent to the Tree being removed.</P1>
<P1>l. On January 24, 2018, the Committee of Adjustments reviewed the written submissions and heard the oral submissions of the Applicants and the Respondents; and the Committee granted the Applicants' request for the minor variances in spite of the Respondents' submissions.</P1>
<P1>m. Allen and Byrne also made application to the City of Toronto, Parks, Forestry &amp; Recreation Division, Urban Forestry Branch (&ldquo;Toronto Urban Forestry&rdquo;) on December 28, 2017 for a permit to destroy the Tree.</P1>
<P1>n. As a precondition to issuance of the permit allowing the Tree to be removed, Applicants were required to erect and submit pictures to Toronto Urban Forestry of Tree Protection Zone hoarding, submit a replacement tree planting plan for approval by Toronto Urban Forestry, and pay a fee in lieu of planting one of three required replacement trees, as there are currently 4 other old and significant Norway Maples at[location omitted]and adding a third replacement tree would have been difficult to accommodate on the already crowded lot.</P1>
<P1>o. The Applicants signed an undertaking on April 19, 2018 in favour of Toronto Urban Forestry undertaking to abide by all conditions related to the issuing of the Tree Destruction Permit, including not destroying any tree prior to receipt of a Building Permit for the project.</P1>
<P1>p. Toronto Urban Forestry issued permit no. S-8662839 on April 19, 2018 to allow Allen and Byrne to have the Tree removed (the &ldquo;Tree Destruction Permit&rdquo;) citing the renovation plan could not be reasonably be completed if the Tree were not removed. The Respondents were copied by Toronto Urban Forestry on the notice issuing the Tree Destruction Permit.</P1>
<P1>q. On June 20, 2018 the City of Toronto issued to Allen and Byrne two building permits for the addition and renovation being: building permit 18 157345 PLB 00 PS; and, building permit 18 157345 BLD 00 SR (collectively, the &ldquo;Building Permits&rdquo;).</P1>
<P1>r. Both Building Permits are based upon the destruction of the Tree in order to complete the addition and renovation.</P1>
<P1>s. The Applicants have taken no action to injure or destroy the Tree but have attempted to comply with all legal requirements and take every reasonable step to diligently advance their renovation project.</P1>
<P1>t. The Tree is a nuisance as it interferes with Allen's and Byrne's use and enjoyment of their property in a substantial way and such interference is unreasonable. The Tree is one of 5 Trees on [location omitted] all of which provide abundant shade and canopy to both properties. Under the Tree Destruction Permit, Applicants are obligated to plant 2 replacement trees, which is a small part of a landscaping plan involving the planting of numerous additional plants, shrubs and trees.</P1>
<P1>u. The addition and renovation to [location omitted] cannot be done in a manner that is reasonably appropriate for the needs of the Applicants unless the Tree is removed.</P1>
<P1>v. It is unreasonable for Allen and Byrne to be denied the full use and enjoyment of their property when the Committee of Adjustments and the City of Toronto have approved the addition and renovation with the removal of the Tree; and Toronto Urban Forestry has issued the Tree Destruction Permit.</P1>
<P1>w. Rules 1.04, 14.05(3)(d), 14.05(3)(e), 14.05(3)(h), 38 and 39 of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>.</P1>
<P1>x. The <EM>Forestry Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990 C. F. 26.</P1>
<P1>y. Such further and other grounds as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P1></P>
<P>3. The following documentary evidence will be used at the hearing of the application:
<P1>a. The Affidavit of Drew Keith Allen sworn on August 30, 2018; and</P1>
<P1>b. Such further and other grounds as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court may permit.</P1></P>
