<BLOCK1><TI>AFFIDAVIT</TI>
<P>I, Meghan Ann MaeDougall, of the City of Toronto, in the Province of Ontario, MAKE OATH AND SAY:</P>
<P>1. I am one of the respondents in this proceeding, and, as such, have knowledge of the matters contained in this affidavit. To the extent that I do not have direct first-hand knowledge of particular facts or events, I have obtained specific information from others, and have indicated the source of that information in my affidavit.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Parties</EM></TI>
<P>2. I am a resident and co-owner of the property municipally known as [location omitted] [location omitted] I have resided at the [location omitted]since 2015. A true copy of the parcel register of[location omitted]is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P>
<P>3. The Applicants, Drew Allen and Susan Byrne, are the residents of the property municipally known as [location omitted] A true copy of the parcel register of [location omitted] is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P>
<P>4. The Applicants have brought this Application to advance a construction project at [location omitted] [location omitted] (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Proposed Construction</BOLD>&rdquo;). The Applicants' plans require the destruction of a boundary tree that is our joint property.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Norway Maple</EM></TI>
<P>5. A mature Norway maple tree, which the Applicants inventoried as &ldquo;tree #5&rdquo; in their construction plans, grows on the boundary line between the [location omitted] (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Norway Maple</BOLD>&rdquo; or the &ldquo;<BOLD>Tree</BOLD>&rdquo;). The Tree creates a natural barrier between the two properties. A survey of [location omitted]created by Vladimir Dosen Surveying dated April 28, 2016 depicts the Tree on the southern boundary with[location omitted] A true copy of that survey is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P>
<P>6. I understand that the Norway Maple is a &ldquo;boundary tree&rdquo; within the meaning of that term in provincial legislation and the common law.</P>
<P>7. The Norway Maple is a healthy, mature tree. Its destruction will fundamentally alter our home, the way we are able to use and enjoy it, and deprive us of one of the things we liked most about our property when we purchased it. The Tree provides many benefits, including cooling, noise reduction, privacy, and shade for our back deck. It is a focal point of our backyard, which we have invested and designed to serve as our primary living space during the summer months. More generally, Nigel and I consider the stewardship of our trees to be an important responsibility in the care of our property, community, and the environment.</P>
<P>8. At paragraph 55 of his Affidavit, Mr. Allen states that the Norway Maple is but one of five large trees that provides shade and canopy to our properties. This statement is misleading. While there are four other mature trees on [location omitted] these provide shade only to the bottom of our garden and our shed, and do not contribute significant shade to our property. Moreover, those are not our trees.</P>
<P>9. An Arbonst Report of Adam Vandermeij (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Vandermeij Report</BOLD>&rdquo;), relied upon by Mr. Allen at Exhibit A to his Affidavit sworn August 30, 2018 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Allen Affidavit</BOLD>&rdquo;) states that the &ldquo;<EM>current proposal</EM> cannot be constructed&rdquo; without destroying the Norway Maple (emphasis mine). At no time have the Applicants provided me with an alternative proposal to the Planned Construction. Nigel and I do not oppose the Applicants' renovation in principle and would not object to a development that accommodates our Tree. Unfortunately, the Applicants have brushed aside our desire to keep a Tree that we consider not only to be rightfully ours but also integral to the character, use, and enjoyment of our home.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Our Decision To Move to</EM>[location omitted]</TI>
<P>10. I moved to Canada from the United Kingdom with my family, Nigel and Dylan, in August 2014. After our arrival in Toronto, I spent several months looking for the right spot for our family to make a home. We settled on the Moore Park neighbourhood. Among the primary factors that drew us to the neighbourhood were its greenery, mature tree canopy, and proximity to the Moore Park Ravine and the Evergreen Brickworks. When we found [location omitted] we were especially taken with its backyard. It is relatively large for a city plot and has enough space for our son, Dylan, and dog to play and for us to entertain. The canopy provided by the Norway Maple was and remains essential to the shade and aesthetic of the yard.</P>
<P>11. Our family moved into[location omitted]in August 2015.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Proposed Construction Project at</EM>[location omitted]</TI>
<P>12. In and around April 2017, Nigel and I began having conversations with the Applicants about a proposed renovation of their home (<EM>i.e.</EM>, the Proposed Construction). It became apparent from these conversations that the destruction and removal of the Norway Maple was a part of the Applicants' plans. Nigel and I made it clear from the outset that we did not want the Tree cut down and that we would not consent to its removal. We told the Applicants that the Norway Maple was too important to us and contributed significantly to our enjoyment of our property.</P>
<P>13. Mr. Allen promised to share the Applicants' construction plans as they developed and became available. Throughout the summer and fall of 2017, Nigel and I periodically asked the Applicants about the status of the Proposed Construction and in particular whether their architect had come up with an alternative design that would preserve the Tree. Neither Applicant gave us a meaningful response&mdash;only that it remained a work in progress of their architects, Tom Spragge + Company Architects Ltd.</P>
<P>14. The Applicants did not provide us with any particulars of the Proposed Construction until mid&mdash;December 2017, when Mr. Allen came to our home with what he referred to as a &ldquo;proposal&rdquo;. I had expected that any plans would be preliminary (given the absence of updates), but to my surprise Mr. Allen presented us with detailed drawings that appeared to be a <EM>fait accompli</EM>.</P>
<P>15. At paragraphs 14 through 20 of his Affidavit, Mr. Allen refers to certain &ldquo;practical issues&rdquo; at[location omitted]that he says animate the Proposed Construction, including lack of proper insulation, risk of flooding, the presence of knob-and-tube-wiring. The drawings that he showed us in mid-December 2017, which are attached at Exhibit C to the Allen Affidavit, included many elaborate features unrelated to these problems. The project provided for major improvements to Mr. Allen and Ms. Byrne's home, such as a new primary kitchen and bedroom, as well as a brand new addition to make room for a walk-out basement, recreational room, an exercise room, music room, mudroom, and guest bedroom with ensuite bathroom.</P>
<P>16. Most significantly, the Applicants' plan for a walk-out basement necessitated the removal of the Norway Maple. Given the advanced stage of planning, it was apparent that the Applicants had known for weeks, if not months, that their planned renovation did not respect our stipulation that the Norway Maple remain intact.</P>
<P>17. Nigel and I immediately conveyed our disappointment to Mr. Allen. He admitted that he had not even asked the architect to try to accommodate the Tree, and that there was no way to keep it while adding all of the features that he and Ms. Byrne wanted.</P>
<P>18. During that same meeting, we discussed ownership of the Norway Maple. Mr. Allen insisted that he had control over the Tree since the majority of it was located on his property. He told us that he could gain access to and remove it without our permission.</P>
<P>19. In late December 2017, Nigel and I received a letter advising us of a Committee of Adjustments meeting to address the Proposed Construction. On December 23, 2017, we wrote to the Applicants to reiterate that we did not consent to the destruction of the Norway Maple. A copy of that correspondence can be found at Exhibit F to the Allen Affidavit.</P>
<P>20. In our December 23 email, Nigel and I reiterated our intention to retain the Tree and reiterated that it adds considerable value to our property and was in fact one of the reasons we chose to live in the neighbourhood. The email also informed the Applicants that the <EM>Forestry Act</EM> contradicted Mr. Allen's assertion that he could destroy the Norway Maple without our consent. We advised that in our view the Tree is a boundary tree within the meaning of the <EM>Forestry Act</EM> and that it could be removed only with our consent.</P>
<P>21. We did not receive a response to our December 23, 2017 email.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Applicants Pursue Approval for their Construction Project Without our Consent</EM></TI>
<P>22. On January 24, 2018, the Committee of Adjustments held a meeting regarding the Minor Variances requested by the Applicants in furtherance of the Proposed Construction. Nigel and I, along with our neighbour, Louise Lang, attended in order to table our objection to the Applicants' plan to remove the Norway Maple. Our appearance was in addition to written objections we sent to the Committee of Adjustments in early January 2018, copies of which appear at Exhibit G to the Allen Affidavit.</P>
<P>23. At the hearing, however, we learned that the Committee of Adjustments was not the proper forum in which to adjudicate the future of the Tree. Specifically, the three-person panel advised us that it did not have jurisdiction to consider the future of the Norway Maple, only the Minor Variances requested by the Applicants. For this reason, we did not appeal when the Committee of Adjustments ultimately approved the Applicants' request for a Minor Variance.</P>
<P>24. As part of the Committee of Adjustments process, Nigel and I participated in a mediation involving the Applicants and their architect, Tom Spragge. Although Nigel and I viewed the mediation as a good faith opportunity to resolve our issues with the Applicants, it was not successful.</P>
<P>25. Nigel and I ceased communications with the Applicants about the Proposed Construction shortly after the January 24, 2018 Committee of Adjustments meeting. In late March 2018, Nigel's father was diagnosed with a severe illness, which disrupted our family life and required Nigel to travel frequently to England.</P>
<P>26. During this period, we received a copy of a letter from Lisa Carson, City of Toronto, Urban Forestry dated March 22, 2018. That letter advised that Urban Forestry had granted the Applicants' application for a permit to remove the Norway Maple. It emphasized, however, that the issuance of a permit &ldquo;does not supersede any civil or common law property rights&rdquo; and that it remained the Applicants' responsibility &ldquo;to resolve any ownership issues or other property disputes&rdquo;. A true copy of Ms. Carson's letter dated March 22, 2018 is attached at <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;D&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P>
<P>27. I understood from Ms. Carson's March 22, 2018 letter that the issuance of a permit was necessary but not sufficient to enable the Applicants to destroy the Norway Maple. Relying on Urban Forestry's communication, Nigel and I decided that we would revisit the matter with the Applicants once Nigel returned from overseas. Unfortunately, we did not have the opportunity to do so until April 2018, when we both returned from his father's funeral.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>The Applicants Commission a Survey Which Shows that the Norway Maple is a Boundary Tree</EM></TI>
<P>28. Immediately on our arrival from England in April 2018, Nigel and I discovered that the Applicants had erected Tree Protection Zone hoarding in front of their house. They could not have done so without accessing our property. The. installation of hoarding prompted us to inquire with the Applicants as to the status of the Proposed Construction.</P>
<P>29. In the conversation that ensued, the Applicants took the position that the City permit allowed them to remove the Norway Maple even without our consent. Nigel and I became concerned that the Applicants either would ignore Urban Forestry's message that we retained our civil and common law and property rights over the Tree or did not acknowledge that we had any such rights. We attempted to discuss the matter further with the Applicants in the ensuing weeks, including by way of an email from Nigel to the Applicants on April 10, 2018, but they refused to engage with us. A true copy of Nigel's email dated April 10, 2018 is attached at <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;E&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P>
<P>30. In this context, we instructed our counsel, Stockwoods, to write to the Applicants to set out in clear terms our position that the Norway Maple is a boundary tree within the meaning of the <EM>Forestry Act</EM>. A copy of that letter, dated April 26, 2018, is located at Exhibit Q to the Allen Affidavit.</P>
<P>31. The Applicants did not contact us against until May 23, 2018, when they emailed to request permission for a surveyor to access our property for the purpose of conducting a laser scan of the Tree in order to confirm that the Tree straddled the property line. We agreed, on the condition that, among other things, the Applicants provide us with a copy of all such reports by the surveyor. A true copy of this email exchange is attached at <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;F&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P>
<P>32. Askan Piller Corporation, Ontario Land Surveyors, conducted a scan of the Norway Maple at 9 a.m. on May 29, 2018. On June 22, 2018, the Applicants' counsel provided us with two images depicting the laser scan of the Norway Maple. These images, which are appended to the Vandermeij Report at Exhibit A to the Allen Affidavit, demonstrate that the Norway Maple straddles the property line between [location omitted]</P>
<P>33. We asked the Applicants to provide us with any reports that accompanied and interpreted the scans of Askan Piller Corporation. Despite these requests, which included the correspondence from our counsel found at Exhibit U to the Allen Affidavit, we did not receive the July 27, 20 18, Vandermeij Report until our counsel was served with the Application Record for this matter on September 5, 2018.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Community Support for Preserving the Norway Maple</EM></TI>
<P>34. We have received a number of communications from members of our community in support of our efforts to resist this Application. These include the following:
<P1>(a) <EM>Letter of Jeremy Gawen, Director of the Moore Park Residents' Association (&ldquo;MPRA&rdquo;)</EM>: In a letter dated November 19, 2018, Mr. Gawen advises, on behalf of the MRPA that the Tree &ldquo;is clearly a boundary tree, is very large and appears to be in excellent condition and we would not wish it to be either damaged or removed.&rdquo; He adds that the MRPA would likely have opposed the Applicants' application for a Minor Variance before the Committee of Adjustment had it known that the Proposed Construction involved the destruction &ldquo;of a beautiful, mature tree on the Boundary with #89&rdquo;. A true copy of Mr. Gawen's letter dated November 19, 2018 is attached at <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;G&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P1>
<P1>(b) <EM>Letter of Louise Lang, owner of</EM>[location omitted] In a letter dated November 26, November 26, 2018, Ms. Lang advises the large trees of the Moore Park neighbourhood, where she has lived for nearly 70 years, add significantly to the area's quality of life. She comments that Tree #5 &ldquo;provides a significant amount of shade for me and my husband&rdquo;. Ms. Lang adds that the tree's root system is beneficial in soaking up rain and melting snow and she fears that its removal could cause more flooding issues on her property. A true copy of Ms. Lang's letter dated November 26, 2018 is attached at <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P1>
<P1>(c)<EM>Letter of Michael Bertouche, owner of</EM>[location omitted] In a letter dated January 5, 2019, Mr. Bertouche advises that he made Applicants aware that he did not support their renovation because he wishes to preserve Moore Park's tree canopy. Mr. Bertouche expresses the hope that the Norway Maple will remain in place. A true copy of Mr. Bertouche's letter dated January 5, 2018 is attached at <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;I&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Response to Certain Allegations About the</EM>[location omitted] <EM>Backyard</EM></TI>
<P>35. The summer after we moved into [location omitted] Nigel and I hired an arborist, Bruce Tree Experts, for the purpose of evaluating the health of our trees. In June 2016, we developed a landscaping project based in part on that assessment.</P>
<P>36. We relied on a landscape designer, Alissa North of North Design Office, Inc. and contractor, Nickolaos Kon of Fossil Landscapes, Ltd. to perform the project, which featured, among other things, the replacement of our back deck, which had rotted and was unsafe. The landscape designer, Ms. North, advised us that she obtained all necessary building permits, and we posted these throughout the project. Ms. North explained that the City did not require a permit to injure because we rebuilt the deck on existing footing installed by the previous owner. A true copy of an invoice from Fossil Landscapes Inc. indicting that our deck was replaced using existing footings is attached at <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;J&rdquo;</BOLD>.</P>
<P>37. At paragraph 62 of his Affidavit, Mr. Allen cites our removal of a tree as part of the deck replacement. Our decision to remove a pear tree was based on the advice of Bruce Tree Experts that the tree was diseased. It had nothing to do with the deck replacement. Ms. North, our landscaper, confirmed that the pear tree was diseased and advised that it was not big enough to require a permit for removal.</P>
<P>38. Nigel and I discussed our plans for our backyard with the Applicants before work began. This discussion included our plans for the deck and the replacement of a fence along our joint property line. The Applicants did not object to any aspect of the project.</P>
<P>
