<BLOCK1><TI>FACTUM OF THE APPLICANTS (Application returnable March 26, 2019)</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. This is an application seeking an Order permitting the removal of a boundary tree located between the properties municipally known as [location omitted] [location omitted] and [location omitted]</P>
<P>2. The boundary tree is a nuisance. The Applicants, like many other home owners in the Moore Park area, wish to modernize their home and add an addition. The Applicants' design requires the removal of the tree. The City of Toronto has approved the Applicants' design and has issued the required building permits. The Committee of Adjustment for the City of Toronto approved the minor variances required for the Applicants' design to be implemented. Most importantly, the City of Toronto, Urban Forestry has issued a Tree Destruction Permit because in order to implement the Applicants' design Urban Forestry found &ldquo;that no reasonable alternatives to tree removal are possible and the tree qualifies for removal under the By-Law.&rdquo;</P>
<P>3. Because the tree is a boundary tree, however, the consent of the Respondents or leave of the Court is required to remove the tree and implement the Tree Destruction Permit. The Respondents have refused to give their consent requiring this Application. The Court should grant the Applicants' request to have the tree removed.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;THE FACTS</TI>
<P>4. The Applicants, Drew Keith Allen (&ldquo;Allen&rdquo;) and Susan Michelle Byrne (&ldquo;Byrne&rdquo;), co-own and reside at the property located at [location omitted]
<P1>- Affidavit of Drew Keith Allen sworn on August 30, 2018 (the &ldquo;Allen Affidavit&rdquo;), Application Record, Tab 2, paras 1-2.</P1></P>
<P>5. The Respondents, Meghan Ann MacDougall (&ldquo;MacDougall&rdquo;) and Nigel Hamid Scott (&ldquo;Scott&rdquo;), are the owners of the property immediately to the north of [location omitted] at [location omitted] [location omitted] are adjoining properties.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 4.</P1></P>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The Tree</EM></TI>
<P>6. There are several large mature trees located on [location omitted]. One of those trees began its growth on[location omitted]and has, over time, grown large enough that it straddles the property line between [location omitted]and[location omitted](the &ldquo;Tree&rdquo;)
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 5.</P1></P>
<P>7. According to a report completed by Adam Vandermeij of Central Tree Care Ltd. (the &ldquo;Vandermeij Report&rdquo;), 78% to 79% of the total trunk and root flare of the Tree are located on [location omitted]and the remaining 21% to 22% are located on [location omitted]. At least 2/3 of the canopy of the Tree overhangs [location omitted].
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 6-7, Exhibits &ldquo;A&rdquo; and &ldquo;B&rdquo;.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>The Proposed Renovations</EM></TI>
<P>8. The Applicants wish to fully use and enjoy [location omitted] by building an appropriate addition and conducting renovations to the existing house situated on the property. The addition and renovations have been contemplated by the Applicants for a very long time.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 8.</P1></P>
<P>9. The Applicants purchased [location omitted] 2001, as a newly married couple. The house on [location omitted] [location omitted] was originally built in approximately 1923.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 9.</P1></P>
<P>10. [location omitted]has sentimental value for the Applicants, as it was the first home they purchased together and it is where all of their three children have grown up. It is also located in the neighbourhood in which all of the Applicant's friends live and where their children's friends live. The Applicants have looked at other homes in Toronto in an attempt to address living space requirements for their growing family, however, they have always decided to stay at [location omitted] [location omitted].
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 12.</P1></P>
<P>11. The Applicants have three children. Since the Applicants' family has grown, the living space limitations of [location omitted]have become more and more apparent.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 13.</P1></P>
<P>12. Currently, the house has three bedrooms. The Applicants share a bedroom and their daughter has her own bedroom. The Applicants' sons, ages twelve and sixteen, currently have to share a bedroom.
<P1>- Cross-examination transcript of Drew Keith Allen on February 12, 2019 (the &ldquo;Allen Cross&rdquo;), p. 24, qs. 229&ndash;233.</P1></P>
<P>13. In contemplation of addressing the limitations of the home, the Applicants met with a number of different house builders over the years to discuss potential renovations, engaged an architectural technologist to prepare some plans for consideration, and viewed many other properties in the Moore Park, Leaside, Rosedale, Lawrence Park and Forest Hill neighbourhoods. As time goes on, the cost of purchasing properties as well as the cost to renovate continues to steadily escalate in the GTA.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraphs 21-22.</P1></P>
<P>14. The Applicants are now in a financial position to proceed with their long-discussed renovation plans.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraphs 25-26.</P1></P>
<P>15. After considering a number of potential architectural design candidates, the Applicants retained the architectural firm of Spragge &amp; Company Architects Ltd. (&ldquo;Spragge &amp; Company&rdquo;) in April 2017 to prepare plans for an addition and renovation to the house.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 28.</P1></P>
<P>16. The Applicants intended to keep as much of the original house as possible and to re -build an addition at the rear of the house in order to try to stay within the size limitations imposed by the City of Toronto By-laws for their lot size and to maintain the look of the house for the benefit of the neighbourhood.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 29.</P1></P>
<P>17. The Applicants and the architect took into account the Tree with respect to the Applicants' renovation plans and they tried to formulate building plans which would meet their needs while preserving the Tree, if at all reasonably possible.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 30.</P1></P>
<P>18. The Applicants asked Spragge &amp; Company whether they would be able to devise a plan which preserves the Tree. However, Spragge &amp; Company was not able to come up with a possible and reasonable plan which would allow the Applicants to preserve the Tree.
<P1>- Allen Cross, p. 32, qs. 214-215.</P1></P>
<P>19. In order to accommodate the Applicants' family living and activity needs, the design prepared by Spragge &amp; Company contemplates adding approximately 1,300 sq. ft. to the existing structure, increasing the gross floor space from approximately 2,400 sq. ft. to 3,700 sq. ft., and repurposing some of the existing space to make it more functional and efficient. Based on other renovation/addition projects that are typically undertaken in the Moore Park neighbourhood with older homes, the size of the addition contemplated by the Applicants is typical of the neighbourhood and the Applicants felt it would be in line with the space requirements to meet their five-person family needs. To be able to accommodate this additional space, the design logically calls for moving the basement foundation walls further towards the rear of[location omitted]
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 31.</P1></P>
<P>20. As the Tree is in very close proximity to the current rear foundation wall of[location omitted]and it and its supporting root structure would be in the direct path of excavation necessary to make the Applicants' proposed renovation achievable, the design calls for the removal of the Tree. If the Tree is preserved, then no addition to the house can be accomplished because any addition, by its very nature, would have to be built on the Tree's existing roots.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 34.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Approval of the Committee of Adjustment</EM></TI>
<P>21. In order to implement the design of the addition and renovation, Spragge &amp; Company made an application on behalf of the Applicants to the Committee of Adjustment in August 2017 to consider approval of minor variances required by the proposed plans.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraphs 35-36, 38, Exhibits &ldquo;D&rdquo; - &ldquo;E&rdquo;.</P1></P>
<P>22. Allen met with the Respondents in mid-December 2017 to advise them of the Applicants' intentions with respect to the proposed renovation and that, regrettably, the renovation plan could not be carried out without seriously impacting the Tree and the Applicants expected they would not be able to preserve the Tree.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 40.</P1></P>
<P>23. The Respondents responded to the Applicants shortly thereafter claiming that they considered the Tree a boundary tree, and that their right to consent was therefore required for the Applicants to be able to remove the Tree. The Respondents advised that they would not consent to such removal and that this was not a negotiable position.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 41, Exhibit &ldquo;F&rdquo;.</P1></P>
<P>24. The Respondents made written submissions to the Committee of Adjustment indicating that, while they did not oppose the planned renovation itself, they wished to voice their claim that the Tree was jointly owned by them and that they would not consent to the Tree being removed.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 42, Exhibit &ldquo;G&rdquo;.</P1></P>
<P>25. On January 24, 2018, the Committee of Adjustment reviewed the written submissions and heard the oral submissions of Spragge &amp; Company on behalf of the Applicants, as well as the submissions of the Respondents and a neighbour backing on to the Respondents' property. The Committee subsequently granted the Applicants' request for the minor variances despite the Respondents' submissions.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 43, Exhibit &ldquo;H&rdquo;.</P1></P>
<P>26. The Respondents did not appeal the decision of the Committee of Adjustment. As such, the decision of the Committee of Adjustment is final and binding.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 44, Exhibit &ldquo;I&rdquo;.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Approval of Toronto Urban Forestry</EM></TI>
<P>27. The Applicants engaged Arborvalley Urban Forestry Co. (&ldquo;Arborvalley&rdquo;) as a consultant to address anticipated tree issues in connection with their renovation. Arborvalley made an application of behalf of the Applicants to the City of Toronto, Parks, Forestry &amp; Recreation Division, Urban Forestry Branch (&ldquo;Toronto Urban Forestry&rdquo;) on December 28, 2017 for a permit to destroy the Tree.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 45, Exhibit &ldquo;J&rdquo;.</P1></P>
<P>28. As a precondition to issuance of the permit allowing the Tree to be remove d, the Applicants were required to erect and submit photographs to Toronto Urban Forestry of Tree Protection Zone hoarding, submit a replacement tree planting plan for approval by Toronto Urban Forestry, and pay a fee in lieu of planting one of three required replacement trees.
