<BLOCK3><TI><EM>City of Toronto Strategic Forest Management Plan</EM></TI>
<P>37. The Respondents retained an arborist, Philip van Wassenaer (&ldquo;van Wassenaer&rdquo;), to prepare a report providing opinion evidence pertaining to the dispute between the Respondents and the Applicants with respect to the nature and benefit of the Tree, as well as the Applicants' ability to develop their property while preserving the tree. Some of the opinions of van Wassenaer are beyond his area of expertise as an arborist.
<P1>- Affidavit of Philip van Wassenaer sworn on January 8, 2019 (the &ldquo;Van Wassenaer Affidavit), Responding Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 3.</P1></P>
<P>38. Van Wassenaer prepared his report dated January 8, 2019 (the &ldquo;Van Wassenaer Report&rdquo;).
<P1>- Van Wassenaer Affidavit, Responding Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 4, Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo;.</P1></P>
<P>39. The Toronto Strategic Forest Management Plan applies to all the trees in the City of Toronto, which includes those in the Moore Park area and, specifically, applies to the Tree at [location omitted] and [location omitted]. As such, Toronto Urban Forestry followed the objectives of the Strategic Forest Management Plan of increasing canopy cover, achieving equitable distribution, increasing biodiversity, increasing awareness, promoting stewardship, and improving monitoring when assessing whether to issue the Tree Destruction Permit. After considering all these objectives and reviewing the circumstances surrounding the Tree, physically inspecting the Tree, and reviewing the Applicants proposed renovation plans, Toronto Urban Forestry determined that it was reasonable to permit the destruction of the Tree.
<P1>- Cross-examination transcript of Philip van Wassenaer on February 13, 2019 (the &ldquo;Van Wassenaer Cross), p. 32, q. 163.</P1></P>
<P>40. Van Wassenaer noted that although he was familiar with the policies under the Toronto Strategic Forest Management Plan to be applied by Toronto Urban Forestry in assessing whether to issue a tree destruction permit, he indicated that he was not aware of whether such processes and policies were followed in assessing and issuing the Tree Destruction Permit to the Applicants. It is submitted that rather than being an impartial expert witness, van Wassenaer has acted as an advocate in this matter. When it was put to him that it was more probable than not that Toronto Urban Forestry considered the impact of removal the Tree would have on shade, energy savings, air quality, animal habitat, storm water reduction, and the entire urban forest; van Wassenaer (despite being put forward as an expert urban arborist) claimed he did not know what the Toronto Urban Forestry inspector took into account. Rather than admitting what is patently obvious as to what any inspector would take into account in determining whether to issue a permit to destroy any tree; van Wassenaer claimed he did not know how Toronto Urban Forestry inspectors make assessments. Van Wassenaer did admit that there was no evidence to suggest that in determining to issue the Tree Destruction Permit that Toronto Urban Forestry did not follow its own policies. If there is no evidence to suggest that Toronto Urban Forestry did not follow its own policies and it is known that the Tree Destruction Permit was issued, then Toronto Urban Forestry made an objective assessment pursuant to the Strategic Forest Management Plan to issue the Tree Destruction Permit.
<P1>- Van Wassenaer Cross, p. 31-32, 42, qs. 158&ndash;163, 195&ndash;208.</P1></P>
<P>41. In addition, the Van Wassenaer Report specifically states the following with respect to the preservation of the Tree (referred to in the Van Wassenaer Report as Tree #5):
<QUOTE><P>It is my professional opinion that the current design has ignored the preservation requirements of Tree #5. There are many different design opportunities which would allow For a significant addition to be built at [location omitted]while respecting the preservation requirements of Tree #5. The applicants have many development configurations available to them that do not further extend the existing foundation of their home into the TPZ [Tree Protection Zone] of Tree #5.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>- Van Wassenaer Affidavit, Responding Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 4, Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo;, page 11.</P1></P>
<P>42. However, on cross-examination, van Wassenaer stated that he is not aware of the specifics of any alternative design options which would be available to the Applicants which would allow them to preserve the Tree, as the formulation of these designs are outside of the scope of his expertise.
<P1>- Van Wassenaer Cross, p. 51, 55- 60, 62, qs. 238, 268&ndash;288, 292.</P1></P>
<P>43. Van Wassnenaer admitted that, although he believed alternative design options could exist, that such options may not provide what the Applicants are seeking. He also admitted that such alternatives may not be compliant with existing by-laws because he is not a land surveyor, architect, or municipal planner.
<P1>- Van Wassenaer Cross, p. 6-7, 60, qs. 15&ndash;24, 288.</P1></P>
<P>44. For example, the permissible length of a house is 17 metres long pursuant to the applicable City of Toronto by-laws. The Applicants' renovation plan proposed a length of 17.77 metres long. This is why a minor variance was required from the Committee of Adjustment. Van Wassenaer states that there is a 6.24 metre tree protection zone surrounding the Tree under Toronto by-laws. He opined that no foundation could be excavated within the tree protection zone without resulting in a risk of damage to the Tree. When van Wassenaer was asked whether he had considered the impact of the tree protection zone along with the 1.22 metre side set backs on either side of[location omitted]upon the increased required length of the house to achieve the same square meterage sought by the Applicants in their proposed renovation plans, van Wassenaer admitted that such an alternative design may not be permissible under the applicable by-laws, as the house length would have to be increased significantly beyond 17.77 metres to accommodate a smaller width.
<P1>- Van Wassenaer Cross, p. 52, 54, 58, 59, qs. 246&ndash;249, 256, 260-261, 279, 284.</P1></P>
<P>45. Despite the above scenario having been put to van Wassenaer on cross-examination, he reiterated that he believed there to be a number of alternative design plans, but that he was not aware of the specifics of such alternatives as the design of same are outside of the scope of his expertise.
<P1>- Van Wassenaer Cross, p. 60, 62, qs. 286&ndash;288, 292.</P1></P>
<P>46. Further, the Respondent MacDougall also admitted on cross-examination that she is not aware of the specifics of any alternative renovation plan which would preserve the Tree. She also indicated that the Respondents have not taken any steps to retain a qualified party to prepare an actual design which would allow for a renovation to the Applicants' home taking into account the 6.24 metre tree protection zone.
<P1>- MacDougall Cross, p. 36, 53-54, qs. 195-196, 284&ndash;287.</P1></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;ISSUES AND THE LAW</TI>
<P>47. The issues on this application are:
<P1>a. whether section 10(3) of the <EM>Forestry Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. F.26 applies in this circumstance;</P1>
<P1>b. whether the Tree constitutes a nuisance to the Applicants; and,</P1>
<P1>c. whether the Applicants can be permitted to remove the Tree without the consent of the Respondents.</P1></P>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Matter brought as Application</EM></TI>
<P>48. <EM>Rule</EM> 14.05(3) of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM> provides the jurisdiction for this matter to be brought as an application. Rules 14.05(3)(d), 14.05(3)(e) and 14.05(3)(h) state:
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(3)</N><TI>Application under Rules</TI>
<SSECP>A proceeding may be brought by application where these rules authorize the commencement of a proceeding by application or where the relief claimed is,</SSECP>
<SSECP>[...]
<PARA><N>(d)</N><PARAP>the determination of rights that depend on the interpretation of a deed will, contract or other instruments, or on the interpretation of a statute, order in council, regulation or municipal by-law or resolution;</PARAP></PARA>
<PARA><N>(e)</N><PARAP>the declaration of an interest in or charge on land, including the nature and extent of the interest of charge or the boundaries of the land, or the settling of the priority of interests or charges;</PARAP></PARA></SSECP>
<SSECP>[...]
<PARA><N>(h)</N><PARAP>in respect of any matter where it is unlikely that there will be any material facts in dispute requiring a trial.</PARAP></PARA></SSECP></SSEC></QUOTE>
<P1>- <EM>Rule 14.05(3)</EM> of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, R.R.O. 1990, Regulation 194, Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;.</P1></P>
<P>49. One of the major issues on this application relates to the interpretation and application of the <EM>Forestry Act</EM>, falling squarely within the scope of <EM>Rule</EM> 14.05(3)(d). As such, this proceeding is appropriately brought by application, as authorized by the <EM>Rules</EM>.
<P1>- <EM>Rule 14.05(3)(d)</EM> of the <EM>Rules of Civil Procedure</EM>, R.R.O. 1990, Regulation 194, Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Application of the Forestry Act</EM></TI>
<P>50. The <EM>Forestry Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. F.26 states the following at section 10(2) with respect to trees growing on the boundary between two properties:
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(2)</N><TI>Trees common property</TI>
<SSECP>Every tree whose trunk is growing on the boundary between adjoining lands is the common property of the owners of the adjoining lands.</SSECP></SSEC></QUOTE>
<P1>- <EM>Forestry Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990 c. F. 26 (the &ldquo;<EM>Forestry Act</EM>&rdquo;), s. 10(2), Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;.</P1></P>
<P>51. Section 10(3) of the <EM>Forestry Act</EM> goes on to state the consequences of destroying such a tree without consent:
<QUOTE><SSEC><N>(3)</N><TI>Offence</TI>
<SSECP>Every person who injures or destroys a tree growing on the boundary between adjoining lands without the consent of the land owners if guilty of an offence under this Act.</SSECP></SSEC></QUOTE>
<P1>- <EM>Forestry Act</EM>, s. 10(3), Schedule &ldquo;B&rdquo;.</P1></P>
<P>52. In <CASEREF><SOC>Hartley v. Cunningham</SOC></CASEREF>, the Court of Appeal upheld the decision of Moore J., who determined on the application that the definition of &ldquo;trunk&rdquo; within the context of the <EM>Forestry Act</EM>, should be given its ordinary dictionary meaning. The Court of Appeal defined trunk:
<QUOTE><P>It is that part of the tree from its point of growth away from its roots up to where it branches out to limbs and foliage. There are no words in the statute that limit the meaning to the &ldquo;trunk&rdquo; at ground level.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>- <CASEREF><SOC>Hartley v. Cunningham</SOC><CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 17445</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, (Juriansz, Hourigan, &amp; Benotto J.J.A.) at para 3, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 1.</P1></P>
<P>53. In <CASEREF><SOC>Hartley v. Cunningham</SOC></CASEREF>, the Court of Appeal further dismissed the appeal, upholding Moore J.'s decision that the applicant could not be declared the sole owner of the tree and that consent of the respondent was required pursuant to section 10 of the <EM>Forestry Act</EM>.
<P1>- <CASEREF><SOC>Hartley v. Cunningham</SOC><CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 17445</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, (Juriansz, Hourigan, &amp; Benotto J.J.A.) at para 4, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 1.</P1></P>
<P>54. However, in <CASEREF><SOC>Freedman v. Cooper</SOC></CASEREF>, Perell J. held that the <EM>Forestry Act</EM> did not apply where the boundary tree constituted a nuisance. In that case, the owner of a property could not obtain the consent of the neighbouring owner to cut down a boundary tree on the properties. As such, Freedman sought an order allowing her to remove the boundary tree, being concerned that without consent from her neighbour, she might be charged under section 10(3) of the <EM>Act</EM> for cutting down the boundary tree. Perell J. concluded that section 10(3) of the <EM>Forestry Act</EM> did not apply under these circumstances, but rather the common law applied. Perell J. applied the common law tort of nuisance, finding that the boundary tree between the properties constituted a nuisance, and as such, Freedman had the right to abate the nuisance by removing the tree.
<P1>- <CASEREF><SOC>Freedman v. Cooper</SOC><CITE>2015 CarswellOnt 2875</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (Perell J.) at paras 29-30, 36, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 2.</P1></P>
<P>55. Perell J. held as follows with respect to a property owner's entitlement to eliminate a continuing nuisance:
<QUOTE><P>Under the law of nuisance, property owners are entitled to resort to self-help remedies to eliminate a <BOLD><EM>continuing nuisance caused by roots and branches from trees</EM></BOLD>, or the court may order that the nuisance by abated or removed. (Emphasis added)</P></QUOTE>
<P1>- <CASEREF><SOC>Freedman v. Cooper</SOC><CITE>2015 CarswellOnt 2875</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (Perell J.) at para 36, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 2.</P1></P>
<P>56. Perell J.'s decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Freedman v. Cooper</SOC></CASEREF> was recently followed by Ricchetti J. in <CASEREF><SOC>Davis v. Sutton</SOC></CASEREF>, wherein Ricchetti J. held:
<QUOTE><P>Accordingly, if the &ldquo;boundary&rdquo; cedars were a nuisance, the <EM>Forestry Act</EM> continues to specify that the boundary tree(s) is jointly owned but the <EM>Forestry Act</EM> does not prohibit a party from taking self-help (or seek a judicial declaration to this effect) where the boundary tree constitutes a nuisance and one co-owner has refused to consent to its removal. In this case the learned trial judge found that the cedars constituted a nuisance and the <EM>Forestry Act</EM> &ldquo;does not apply in this case&rdquo;. Having found that the cedars constituted a nuisance, the trial judge's conclusion by the learned trial judge is consistent with the applicable legal authorities.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>- <CASEREF><SOC>Davis v. Sutton</SOC><CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 5533</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (Ricchetti J.) at para 41, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 3.</P1></P>
<P>57. Ricchetti J. further held:
<QUOTE><P>In my view, a co-owner of a boundary tree causing a nuisance to the other co-owner cannot use an unreasonable refusal to consent to cutting the tree to prevent the abatement of the nuisance.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>- <CASEREF><SOC>Davis v. Sutton</SOC><CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 5533</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (Ricchetti J.) at para 45, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 3.</P1></P>
<P>58. As such, if a boundary tree constitutes a nuisance to one of the co-owners of the tree, consent pursuant to section 10(3) of the <EM>Forestry Act</EM> is not required for the removal of the tree.</P>
<P>59. In the present case, the Tree is currently growing on both[location omitted]and[location omitted] As such, as held by Ricchetti J. in <CASEREF><SOC>Davis v. Sutton</SOC></CASEREF>, section 10(2) of the <EM>Forestry Act</EM> continues to specify that the Tree is common property between the Applicants and the Respondents. However, further to the decisions in both <CASEREF><SOC>Davis v. Sutton</SOC></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>Freedman v. Cooper</SOC></CASEREF>, if the Tree is held to constitute a nuisance to the Applicants, section 10(3) of the <EM>Forestry Act</EM> does not prohibit the Applicants from taking steps to abate the nuisance by removing the Tree where the Respondents continue to refuse to provide their consent.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Nuisance</EM></TI>
<P>60. According to the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Antrim Truck Centre v. Ontario (Ministry of Transportation)</SOC></CASEREF>, for there to be a nuisance, there must be an interference with a property owner's use and enjoyment of their property and such interference must be substantial and unreasonable:
<QUOTE><P>The elements of a claim in private nuisance have often been expressed in terms of a two-part test of this nature: to support a claim in private nuisance the interference with the owner's use or enjoyment of land must be both <EM>substantial</EM> and <EM>unreasonable</EM>. A substantial interference with property is one that is non-trivial. Where this threshold is met, the inquiry proceeds to the reasonableness analysis, which is concerned with whether the non-trivial interference was also unreasonable in all of the circumstances.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>- <CASEREF><SOC>Antrim Truck Centre Ltd. v. Ontario (Ministry of Transportation)</SOC><CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 2354</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (McLachlin C.J.C., LeBel, Fish, Abella, Rothstein, Cromwell, Moldaver, Karakatsanis, Wagner J.J.) at paras 18-19, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 4.</P1></P>
<P>61. In <CASEREF><SOC>Davis v. Sutton</SOC></CASEREF>, the appellants argued that boundary trees should only constitute a nuisance if there is imminent danger of damage being caused, damage has been actually caused, or in cases of emergency. Ricchetti J., however, held that there was no reason to impose such a special category limiting common law nuisance in the context of boundary trees and that the normal test for nuisance applied.
<P1>- <CASEREF><SOC>Davis v. Sutton</SOC><CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 5533</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (Ricchetti J.) at para 53, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 3.</P1></P>
<P>62. Ricchetti J. further held that the existing cedars on the boundary line between the respondent's property and the appellant's adjoining property constituted a substantial interference, as the cedars prevented the respondents from constructing a fence in their backyard for the safety of a six-year old child living at the respondent's property without losing approximately six to eight feet of their backyard. The position, angles, and size of the cedars contributed to the substantial and unreasonable nature of the interference with the respondent's full use and enjoyment of his property, as the respondent &ldquo;had every right [...] to use his property for the safety and enjoyment of the 6 year old child&rdquo;. Similarly, the Applicants wish to have the full use and enjoyment of their property by constructing an addition which has been approved by the granting of building permits and by the Committee of Adjustment. The Tree is causing a substantial and unreasonable interference with the Applicants' full use and enjoyment of[location omitted]
<P1>- <CASEREF><SOC>Davis v. Sutton</SOC><CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 5533</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (Ricchetti J.) at paras 49, 51, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 3.</P1></P>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Substantial Interference</EM></TI>
<P>63. In <CASEREF><SOC>Antrim Truck Centre Ltd. v. Ontario (Ministry of Transportation)</SOC></CASEREF>, Cromwell J. described the threshold of substantial interference as follows:
<QUOTE><P>What does this threshold require? In <EM>Barette</EM>, the Court noted that the requirement of substantial harm &ldquo;means that compensation will not be awarded for trivial annoyances&rdquo;: para 77. In <EM>St. Pierre</EM>, while the Court was careful to say that the categories of nuisance are not closed, it also noted that only interferences that &ldquo;<UNDER>substantially</UNDER> alte[r] the nature of the claimant's property itself&rdquo; or interfere &ldquo;to a <UNDER>significant</UNDER> extent with the actual use being made of the property are sufficient to ground a claim in nuisance: p. 915 (emphasis added). One can ascertain from these authorities that a substantial injury to the complainant's property interest is one that amounts to more than a slight annoyance or trifling interference. As La Forest J. put it in <CASEREF><SOC>Tock v. St. John's (City) Metropolitan Area Board</SOC><CITE>[1989] 2 S.C.R. 1181</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, actionable nuisances include &ldquo;only those inconveniences that materially interfere with ordinary comfort as defined according to the standards held by those of plain and sober tastes&rdquo;, and not claims based &ldquo;on the prompting of excessive &lsquo;delicacy and fastidiousness&rsquo;&rdquo;: p. 1191. Claims that are clearly of this latter nature do not engage the reasonableness analysis.</P>
<P>In referring to these statements I do not mean to suggest that there are firm categories of types of interference which determine whether an interference is or is not actionable, a point I will discuss in more detail later. Nuisance may take a variety of forms and may include not only actual physical damage to land but also interference with the health, comfort or convenience of the owner or occupier: <EM>Tock</EM>, at pp. 1190-91. The point is not that there is a typology of actionable interferences; the point is rather that there is a threshold of seriousness that must be met before an interference is actionable.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>- <CASEREF><SOC>Antrim Truck Centre Ltd. v. Ontario (Ministry of Transportation)</SOC><CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 2354</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (McLachlin C.J.C., LeBel, Fish, Abella, Rothstein, Cromwell, Moldaver, Karakatsanis, Wagner J.J.) at paras 22-23, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 4.</P1></P>
<P>64. As such, <EM>Antrim Truck Centre Ltd</EM>., identifies substantial interference as one which interferes significantly with the use made of the property and is not just a &ldquo;trifling interference&rdquo;. The Supreme Court of Canada acknowledges that nuisance may include an interference to the comfort and convenience of the property owner or occupier.</P>
<P>65. The Tree is a substantial interference with the Applicants' use and enjoyment of their property. Since purchasing [location omitted], the Applicants' family has grown from two to five members. The Applicants seek to undertake the proposed renovations to improve the space occupied by their family, and to accommodate their everyday lives at [location omitted] given their increased family size.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 8, 13, 31.</P1></P>
<P>66. There is no other feasible opportunity for the addition to be completed without the removal of the Tree. The Applicants have inquired of their architect, Spragge &amp; Company, as to whether their proposed renovation goals could be met while preserving the Tree, however, they have been advised by Spragge &amp; Company that no reasonable such plans can be devised to do so. The only acceptable renovation plan available to the Applicants requires the removal of the Tree.
<P1>- Allen Cross, p. 32, qs. 214-215.</P1>
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraphs 30, 34.</P1></P>
<P>67. Although the Respondents have taken the position that there are alternative design options available to the Applicants which preserve the Tree, they have provided no evidence to support this assertion. In addition, van Wassenaer admitted on cross-examination that he was not aware of the specifics of any such alternative plan and that alternative plans could be limited due to the applicable municipal by-laws.
<P1>- Van Wassenaer Cross, p. 6-7, 60, 62, qs. 15&ndash;24, 286&ndash;288, 292.</P1>
<P1>- MacDougall Cross, p. 36, 53-54, qs. 195-196, 284&ndash;287.</P1></P>
<P>68. The presence of the Tree continues to prevent the Applicants from fully using and enjoying [location omitted] given their increased family by completing the approved addition.</P>
<P>69. Further, due to the age of the home, these renovations would not only allow the home to be brought up to modem living standards to accommodate the family's needs, but also to realize the home's foil property value. If the Applicants are prevented from moving forward with their renovation plans, they will not be able to realize the home's foil market value if it were to be sold in its current state.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraph 12.</P1></P>
<P>70. The Tree constitutes a substantial interference as described by the Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>Antrim Truck Centre Ltd</EM>., as it significantly interferes with the Applicants' ability to use their property in a manner which accommodates the needs of their family. It continues to drastically affect the comfort and convenience of the Applicants and their family by preventing the realization of the foil functionality and space their property could provide and as permitted by the Committee of Adjustment. Due to the presence of a substantial interference, the Applicants' case passes the threshold stage of the nuisance analysis.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><TI><EM>Unreasonableness</EM></TI>
<P>71. The Supreme Court of Canada described how the &ldquo;unreasonableness&rdquo; portion of the test for nuisance is to be applied in <CASEREF><SOC>Antrim Truck Centre Ltd. v. Ontario (Ministry of Transportation)</SOC></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>[...] As in other private nuisance cases, the reasonableness of the interference must be assessed in light of all of the relevant circumstances. The focus of that balancing exercise, however, is on whether the interference is such that it would be unreasonable in all of the circumstances to require the claimant to suffer it without compensation.</P>
<P>In the traditional law of private nuisance, the courts assess, in broad terms, whether the interference is unreasonable by balancing the gravity of the harm against the utility of the defendant's conduct in all of the circumstances [...] The Divisional Court and the Court of Appeal identified several factors that have often been referred to in assessing whether a substantial interference is also unreasonable. In relation to the gravity of the harm, the courts have considered factors such as the severity of the interference, the character of the neighbourhood and the sensitivity of the plaintiff [...] The frequency and duration of an interference may also be relevant in some cases. [...]</P></QUOTE>
<P1>- <CASEREF><SOC>Antrim Truck Centre Ltd. v. Ontario (Ministry of Transportation)</SOC><CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 2354</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (McLachlin C.J.C., LeBel, Fish, Abella, Rothstein, Cromwell, Moldaver, Karakatsanis, Wagner J.J.) at paras 25-26, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 4.</P1></P>
<P>72. The Supreme Court of Canada does, however, caution that these factors are not a checklist, and are only some of the criteria to be reviewed with respect to the tort of nuisance.
<P1>- <CASEREF><SOC>Antrim Truck Centre Ltd. v. Ontario (Ministry of Transportation)</SOC><CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 2354</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (McLachlin C.J.C., LeBel, Fish, Abella, Rothstein, Cromwell, Moldaver, Karakatsanis, Wagner J.J.) at para 26, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 4.</P1></P>
<P>73. The Supreme Court further clarifies that the focus is on the unreasonableness of the interference, and not on whether the defendant's conduct is unreasonable. However, the conduct of a defendant is not an irrelevant consideration, particularly where such conduct is malicious or careless.
<P1>- <CASEREF><SOC>Antrim Truck Centre Ltd. v. Ontario (Ministry of Transportation)</SOC><CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 2354</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (McLachlin C.J.C., LeBel, Fish, Abella, Rothstein, Cromwell, Moldaver, Karakatsanis, Wagner J.J.) at para 28, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 4.</P1></P>
<P>74. Another relevant factor identified in <CASEREF><SOC>Antrim Truck Centre Ltd. v. Ontario (Ministry of Transportation)</SOC></CASEREF> for consideration with respect to private nuisance is the duration of the interference, stating:
<QUOTE><P>While temporary interferences may certainly support a claim in nuisance in some circumstances, interferences that persist for a prolonged period of time will be more likely to attract a remedy [...]</P></QUOTE>
<P1>- <CASEREF><SOC>Antrim Truck Centre Ltd. v. Ontario (Ministry of Transportation)</SOC><CITE>2013 CarswellOnt 2354</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (McLachlin C.J.C., LeBel, Fish, Abella, Rothstein, Cromwell, Moldaver, Karakatsanis, Wagner J.J.) at para 42, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 4.</P1></P>
<P>75. In the present case, the interference of the Tree upon the Applicants' use and enjoyment of their property is unreasonable. Firstly, if the Tree is not permitted to be removed, the Applicants will continue to suffer this substantial interference on an indefinite basis while they own the property. Unless the Tree is removed, the Applicants will never be able to attain the functionality and space they require to meet the needs of their family at [location omitted]and build the addition which has been approved by the City of Toronto Building Department, the Committee of Adjustment, and Toronto Urban Forestry. Further, the Applicants will never be able to realize the full market value of their property. The permanent and ongoing nature of the interference upon the Applicants is entirely unreasonable.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraphs 12, 13, 30, 43, 50, 53, Exhibits &ldquo;H&rdquo;, &ldquo;P&rdquo;, &ldquo;R&rdquo; - &ldquo;S&rdquo;.</P1></P>
<P>76. A further consideration is a balancing of the extent of the harm against the Applicants against the effect of removing the Tree causing the nuisance. As noted above, the harm imposed upon the Applicants is significant and such harm outweighs the effect of the removal of the Tree. The Respondents have noted that they derive benefits from the Tree, including shade and cooling effects upon their home. However, these benefits do not outweigh the effect imposed upon the Applicants if they continue to be unable to undertake their renovation to meet the needs of their family, as it impacts the Applicants' ability to fully use and enjoy their property.
<P1>- Allen Affidavit, Application Record, Tab 2, paragraphs 8, 65.</P1>
<P1>- Affidavit of Meghan Ann MacDougall sworn on January 8, 2019, Responding Application Record, Tab 1, paragraph 7.</P1>
<P1>- MacDougall Cross, p. 41&ndash;43, qs. 224&ndash;233.</P1></P>
<P>77. It is submitted that in issuing the Tree Destruction Permit, Toronto Urban Forestry engaged in an objective analysis, after physically inspecting the Tree, to determine whether the Tree should be removed. In reaching its decision, Toronto Urban Forestry evaluated the criteria set out in the Strategic Forest Management Plan. After engaging in this analysis, Toronto Urban Forestry concluded that the renovations could not allow for the preservation of the Tree and it approved of the Tree's removal.
<P1>- Van Wassenaer Cross, p. 31-32, 42, qs. 158&ndash;163, 195&ndash;208.</P1></P>
<P>78. As stated by Ricchetti J. in <CASEREF><SOC>Davis v. Sutton</SOC></CASEREF>, the interference need not cause imminent danger, have caused actual damage, or cause emergency circumstances in order for a tree to be a nuisance. Ricchetti J. concluded that the inability to use a property owner's backyard in a manner in a way desired by the property owner was a nuisance caused by a tree. Similarly the Tree causes an unreasonable interference to the Applicants' ability to use and enjoy their property and, as such, is a nuisance.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Davis v. Sutton</SOC><CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 5533</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (Ricchetti J.) at paras 49&ndash;51, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 3.</P1></P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI><EM>Removal of the Tree</EM></TI>
<P>79. It is well-established at common law that property owners are entitled to resort to self-help remedies to eliminate a nuisance caused by tree branches or roots growing from an adjoining property. In <CASEREF><SOC>Graham v. Da Silva</SOC></CASEREF>, McDermid Co. Ct. J. (as he then was) held that Da Silva was entitled to remove a branch leaning over his property, although the tree was growing entirely on Graham's neighbouring property. The removal of the overhanging branch caused the tree to split down into the trunk, resulting in the need for the entire tree to be removed. McDermid Co. Ct. J., (as he then was), further determined that it was of no consequence that Da Silva ultimately had to cut down the entire tree, and that Da Silva was entitled to do so in order to abate the nuisance.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Graham v. Da Silva</SOC><CITE>1984 CarswellOnt 603</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. Co. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (McDermid Co. Ct. J.) at paras 5-6, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 5.</P1></P>
<P>80. The decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Graham v. Da Silva</SOC></CASEREF> was followed by Arbour J., (as she then was), in <CASEREF><SOC>Centrum Land Corporation v. Institute of Chartered Accountants of Ontario et al</SOC></CASEREF>. In that case, the defendant wished to expand the building on their property and in order to do so, would need to remove a number of trees which grew along the boundary line with the plaintiff's neighbouring property. The defendant had obtained a building permit for the addition. Centrum sought a permanent injunction restraining the defendant from destroying the trees.
<P1>- <CASEREF><SOC>Centrum Land Corporation v. Institute of Chartered Accountants of Ontario et al.</SOC><CITE>1988 CarswellOnt 193</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. H.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (Arbour J.) at paras 1, 3, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 6.</P1></P>
<P>81. Arbour J. concluded that the defendant was entitled to remove the trees on the basis that they were a nuisance which prevented it from being able to move forward with the addition. In reaching this decision, Arbour J. stated:
<QUOTE><P>[...] A tree that encroaches on that boundary line may become a nuisance to the adjacent owner. In such case, at common law, the owner would be entitled to take measures to suppress that nuisance. [...]</P></QUOTE>
<P1>- <CASEREF><SOC>Centrum Land Corporation v. Institute of Chartered Accountants of Ontario et al.</SOC><CITE>1988 CarswellOnt 193</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. H.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (Arbour J.) at para 9, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 6.</P1></P>
<P>82. In following the decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Graham v. Da Silva</SOC></CASEREF> and permitting the removal of the trees, Arbour J. stated:
<QUOTE><P>[...] It would seem to me to be a fair analysis of the problem in this case to examine the situation that the institute would be in if the trees which will be affected by its construction project were entirely on Centrum's land. To put it another way, I would have thought that Centrum could have no greater right in the trees on the boundary line than it would have if the trees were completely on its land.</P>
<P>If this were the case, the institute would clearly be entitled, in my opinion, to remove any branches or roots of such trees which interfere with the peaceful enjoyment of its property, including the right to build on it within an inch of the boundary line. [...] If the tree is so close to the boundary line that the cutting back of the offending branches or roots is likely to jeopardize the ability of the tree to survive the cut, I was referred to no authority which suggests that the adjacent owner must then suffer the nuisance. I agree with the disposition of <CASEREF><SOC>Graham v. Da Silva</SOC></CASEREF> which imposed no such limitations in similar circumstances.</P>
<P>It goes without saying that if the trees in this case were located entirely on the institute's land, they could be removed by the institute despite their shade and ornamental value to the plaintiff's tenant. If the trees were located entirely on Centrum's land, the institute could remove any part of them which would interfere with its construction plans. Absent the provisions of the <EM>Trees Act</EM>, which clearly do not apply in this case, I cannot see how the situation can be different merely because the trees happen to grow on the boundary line.</P></QUOTE>
<P1>- <CASEREF><SOC>Centrum Land Corporation v. Institute of Chartered Accountants of Ontario et al.</SOC><CITE>1988 CarswellOnt 193</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. H.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (Arbour J.) at paras 20&ndash;22, Book of Authorities of the Applicant, Tab 6.</P1></P>
<P>83. The facts in <EM>Centrum Land Corporation</EM> are completely analogous to those in the present case. The Applicants wish to undergo a renovation which includes the construction of an addition to their property. The Tree prohibits the Applicants from being able to move forward with the renovation. As in <EM>Centrum Land Corporation</EM>, the Applicants have obtained the appropriate Building Permits and Tree Destruction Permit. Further, the <EM>Trees Act</EM> (the predecessor of the <EM>Forestry Act</EM>) did not have any application in <EM>Centrum Land Corporation</EM> and Arbour J. relied upon the common law in determining that the defendants could remove the trees.</P>
<P>84. Following the holding of Arbour J., the Applicants would be able to abate the nuisance caused by the Tree by cutting any roots or branches which affected the Applicants' property or proposed renovation if the trunk of the Tree was entirely situated on the Respondents' property. At common law, they could do this without the Respondents consent. If the trunk was entirely situated on the Applicants' property, then they could abate the nuisance without the Respondents consent. The Applicants should not be prevented from being able to abate the nuisance caused to them by the Tree solely because the Tree is located on the boundary line between their property and that of the Respondents. No case has ever held this and, in fact, Arbour J. held the complete opposite in <EM>Centrum Land Corporation</EM>.</P>
<P>85. Given that the <EM>Forestry Act</EM> does not apply to require the consent of the Respondents due to the nuisance caused by the Tree, the Applicants are entitled to take steps to abate such nuisance by removing the Tree in order to proceed with their renovation plans.</P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P>86. The Applicants respectfully request:
<P1>a. An Order permitting the removal of the boundary tree located between the property located at [location omitted]and[location omitted]</P1>
<P1>b. Pre-judgment interest and post-judgment interest pursuant to the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, R.S.O. 1990, c. C-43, as amended;</P1>
<P1>c. Costs of this application;</P1>
<P1>d. Such further and other relief as counsel may advise and this Honourable Court permit.</P1></P>
