<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;INTRODUCTION</TI>
<P>1. The Applicants, Drew Allen and Susan Byrne, and the Respondents, Meghan MacDougall and Nigel Scott, are neighbours in the Moore Park neighbourhood of Toronto. The Applicants assert that they should be permitted to destroy the Respondents' property in order to enhance the value of their own.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Transcript of the Cross-Examination of Drew Allen, February 12, 2019 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Allen Transcript</BOLD>&rdquo;), P. 37 QQ. 256&ndash;259, Transcript Brief, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The property at issue, a large Norway Maple (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Maple</BOLD>&rdquo; or the &ldquo;<BOLD>Tree</BOLD>&rdquo;), is a boundary tree that straddles the property line between the Respondents' and the Applicants' properties. As such, the Maple is co-owned by both sets of neighbours. The Applicants acknowledge that the Tree is co-owned and that the Respondents possess a property interest in the Tree. But the Applicants are intent on building a 1300-square-foot addition to their home, and they do not believe that inconveniences such as other people's property rights should get in their way.</P>
<P>2. The Respondents do not oppose the Applicants renovating their home. The Respondents ask only that the Applicants pursue their renovations in a manner that preserves the Maple&mdash;an integral part of the Respondents' home and one of the reasons they purchased it in the first place.</P>
<P>3. Rather than alter their renovation plans and attempt to reach a good-faith compromise with the Respondents that preserves the Tree, the Applicants come to this Court and ask it to declare the Maple a nuisance. This Court ought to decline their invitation.</P>
<P>4. The Applicants mischaracterize the Maple as an impediment to improving their home. The Maple does not affect renovations within Applicants' existing residence or prevent them from resolving the &ldquo;practical issues&rdquo; they describe in their affidavit evidence. The Maple impacts only the Applicants' plan for a walkout basement, which is part of their 1300-square-foot addition to the home. The Respondents' expert, Philip van Wassenaer, an experienced consulting arborist, provided evidence that the Applicants' proposed renovation and the Maple can coexist if the Applicants reduce the contemplated below-grade excavation to one side of their property.</P>
<P>5. The existence of a large and healthy Maple in a neighbourhood renowned for its tree canopy is not a nuisance. There is no risk of harm or damage to the Applicants or their property. The Applicants can <EM>substantially</EM> improve and enlarge their home with the Maple intact. They are simply required to do so in a way that differs from their current plans. The Applicants may feel that exploring alternative design options is inconvenient, but living in an urban neighbourhood (or in any society) requires respect for other people's property rights. This Court ought not condone the Applicants' exceptionalism. The Application should be dismissed with costs.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;SUMMARY OF FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>Background</TI>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>(i)</EM></N><TI><EM>The Parties</EM></TI>
<P>6. The Respondents Meghan MacDougall and Nigel Scott, have owned and resided at the property municipally known as [location omitted] since 2015.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Meghan MacDougall dated January 8, 2019 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>MacDougall Affidavit</BOLD>&rdquo;) at para. 2, Respondents Application Record (&ldquo;<BOLD>RAR</BOLD>&rdquo;), Tab 1, pp. 1-2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Their next-door neighbours, the Applicants Susan Byrne and Drew Allen, own and reside at the adjacent property to the south, [location omitted].<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MacDougall Affidavit at para. 3, RAR, Tab 1, p. 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Maple grows on the southern boundary line between the [location omitted] and creates a natural barrier between the two properties.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MacDougall Affidavit at para. 4, RAR, Tab 1, p. 2; Survey of[location omitted]dated April 28, 2016, McDougall Affidavit, Exhibit C, RAR, Tab 1, p. 19.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>(ii)</EM></N><TI><EM>The Evidence on this Application</EM></TI>
<P>7. Drew Allen, one of the Applicants, swore an affidavit dated August 30, 2018 and attended cross-examination on February 12, 2019. Meghan MacDougall, one of the Respondents, swore an affidavit dated January 8, 2019 and attended cross-examination on February 26, 2019. Neither Mr. Allen nor Ms. MacDougall is or purports to be an expert in matters of architecture, engineering, arboriculture, or urban planning.</P>
<P>8. There is only one source of expert evidence on this Application, in the form of the affidavit of Philip van Wassenaer and his accompanying report dated January 8, 2019 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>van Wassenaer Report</BOLD>&rdquo;). Mr. van Wassenaer attended cross-examination on February 13, 2019.</P>
<P>9. Mr. van Wassenaer is an expert in the areas of arboriculture and urban forestry with over 28 years of experience.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Arborist Report&mdash;<CASEREF><SOC>Allen-Byrne v. MacDougall-Scott</SOC></CASEREF> dated January 8, 2019, (the &ldquo;<BOLD>van Wassenaer Report</BOLD>&rdquo;) at p. 2, Affidavit Philip van Wassenaer sworn January 8, 2019 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>van Wassenaer Affidavit</BOLD>&rdquo;), Exhibit B, RAR, Tab 2B, p. 51.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He was a practising arborist for ten years, during which time he undertook a full range of arboricultural operations commonly employed in urban areas. Since 1999, he has been continuously employed as a consulting urban forester and consulting arborist. Mr. van Wassenaer's role as a consulting arborist requires him to be aware of engineering, architecture, and landscape architecture and their impact on trees. His projects often require him to work with engineers and architects to determine how a tree can be preserved in building projects.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Transcript of the Cross-Examination of Philip van Wassenaer, February 13, 2019 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>van Wassenaer Transcript</BOLD>&rdquo;), PP. 50-51, QQ. 237, Transcript Brief, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>10. The Applicants did not respond to the van Wassenaer Report. They have tendered no evidence, expert or otherwise, from their architect, Tom Spragge, or either of their arborists, Adam Vandermeij and Mark Procunier. Nor have they put forward evidence regarding the practices of Toronto Urban Forestry, either generally or in the specific circumstances of this case.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>The Applicants Ignored the Respondents' Request To Preserve the Tree</TI>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>(i)</EM></N><TI><EM>The Maple Is an Important Feature of the Respondents' Home</EM></TI>
<P>11. The Maple is valuable to the Respondents and integral to their home. According to Ms. MacDougall, who by profession is a conservationist with the W. Garfield Weston Foundation with a degree in Wildlife Biology and Natural Resources Management,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Transcript of the Cross-Examination of Meghan MacDougall, February 26, 2019 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>MacDougall Transcript</BOLD>&rdquo;), P. 3, Q. 5; P. 5, Q. 20, Transcript Brief, Tab 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> she and her family consider the stewardship of their trees, generally, to be an important responsibility in the care of their property, community, and the environment.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MacDougall Affidavit at para. 7, RAR, p. 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>12. After moving to Canada in 2014, the Respondents decided to move to Moore Park in large part because of its greenery, mature tree canopy, and proximity to the Moore Park Ravine and the Evergreen Brickworks.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>. at para. 10, RAR p. 3</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> They are not alone in their impression of the neighbourhood. Louise Lang, the parties' neighbour to the west, comments in a letter, &ldquo;One of the biggest attractions of Moore Park is the large trees, especially the &lsquo;Century&rsquo; or &lsquo;Granddaddy&rsquo; trees. These large trees of Moore Park add significantly to the quality of life in this neighbourhood for the shade and aesthetic beauty they provide.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter form Louise Lang dated November 26, 2018 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Lang Letter</BOLD>&rdquo;), MacDougall Affidavit, Exhibit H, RAR, p. 35.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>13. The Respondents' home, [location omitted], embodies the characteristics that drew them to the neighbourhood. They were especially attracted to its backyard. It is relatively large for a city plot and has enough space to entertain outdoors and for then son to play. The Maple was one of the things the Respondents liked most about [location omitted] at the time they purchased the property in the summer of 2015.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MacDougall Affidavit at para. 7, RAR, p. 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The canopy provided by the Tree was and remains essential to the shade and aesthetic of the yard,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MacDougall Affidavit at para. 10, RAR, p. 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> which the Respondents have designed to serve as their primary living space during the summer months.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MacDougall Affidavit at para. 7, RAR, p. 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>14. The Applicants state in their factum that the Maple is but one of five large trees that provides shade and canopy to [location omitted].<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Applicants' factum, para. 35.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This statement is misleading. While there are four other mature trees on [location omitted], these provide shade only to the bottom of the Respondents' garden and their shed, and do not contribute significant shade to their property.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MacDougall Affidavit at para. 8, RAR, p. 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Moreover, those trees are not the Respondents' property.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>15. A neighbour, Ms. Lang, describes the Maple's canopy as &ldquo;truly a magnificent sight.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Lang Letter, MacDougall Affidavit, Exhibit H, RAR, p. 35.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Another neighbour, Michael Bertouche, advises, &ldquo;I believe the beauty of Moore Park and the tree canopy is special and valuable to this community and needs to be preserved.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter of Michael Bertouche dated January 5, 2019 (&ldquo;Bertouche Letter&rdquo;), MacDougall Affidavit, Exhibit 1, RAR p. 37.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He adds, &ldquo;I am hopeful that the tree will remain in place at the end of this process.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Ibid.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Similarly, the Director of the Moore Park Residents' Association, Jeremy Gawen, notes that the Maple &ldquo;is very large and appears to be in excellent condition and we would not wish it to be either damaged or removed.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter of Jeremy Gawen dated November 19, 2019 [<EM>sic</EM>] (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Gawen Letter</BOLD>&rdquo;), MacDougall Affidavit, Exhibit G, RAR p. 32.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>(ii)</EM></N><TI><EM>The Maple Holds Real Value for the Applicants</EM></TI>
<P>16. The Maple is a vibrant and healthy tree and objectively valuable. The Tree generates numerous benefits for [location omitted] and its surroundings.</P>
<P>17. As set out more fully in his report, Mr. van Wassenaer appraised the Maple using the Trunk Formula Method.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Van Wassenaer Report at p. 7, RAR, p. 56.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This technique calculates a tree's value as a function of, among other things, its size, condition, species, location, and the cost of installation. On this basis, Mr. van Wassenaer concluded that the Maple has a quantifiable monetary value of $46,200.</P>
<P>18. Mr. van Wassenaer notes that the Maple provides several significant additional benefits to the use, enjoyment, and value of the Respondents' property. Among the specific benefits that Mr. van Wassenaer notes in his report:
<P1>(a) <EM>Shade</EM>:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>. at p. 5, RAR, p. 54.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Mature Norway maple trees cast dense shade, which has multiple ancillary benefits. As the only large-stature tree in the rear yard of the property at [location omitted] the Maple's large and full canopy casts shade across the house and backyard for a considerable portion of the day. The Tree's removal would add another four to six hours of light to [location omitted]and eliminate afternoon shade altogether, which would make the backyard far less hospitable during the warmer summer months.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Arborist Report of Adam Vandermeij (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Vandermeij Report</BOLD>&rdquo;), Affidavit of Drew Allen sworn August 30, 2018 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Allen Affidavit</BOLD>&rdquo;), Exhibit A, Application Record dated August 31, 2018 (&ldquo;<BOLD>AR</BOLD>&rdquo;), p. 28.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(b) <EM>Energy Savings</EM>:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Van Wassenaer Report at pp. 5-6, RAR, pp 54-55.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Tree shade reduces solar heating, and evapotranspiration through tree leaves helps cool the local microclimate. Due to its close proximity to the house at [location omitted] and the shade it casts, the Maple reduces energy use demand.</P1>
<P1>(c) <EM>Air Quality</EM>:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>. at p. 6, RAR, p. 55.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Maple likely contributes to improved local air quality and physical wellbeing by dry deposition of particulate pollutants, such as soot from vehicle exhaust, and the chemical processing of pollutants. This direct effect on air quality contributes to the Respondents' and their guests' enjoyment of the rear patio and backyard where they spend considerable time in the summer months.</P1>
<P1>(d) <EM>Property Value and Aesthetics</EM>:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>. at p. 6, RAR, p. 55.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Mature and healthy trees can significantly increase the value of residential and commercial properties, largely due to their aesthetic appeal. The neighbourhood around Hudson Drive is characterized by a large and healthy tree canopy, which contributes to its desirability and livability. The Maple contributes to the value of the property at [location omitted] due to its aesthetic appeal.</P1>
<P1>(e) <EM>Habitat</EM>:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>. at p. 6, RAR, p. 55.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Urban trees provide valuable habitat and refugia for a wide range of species, such as insects, birds and small mammals, and one of the most important habitat functions of mature urban trees in Toronto is the provision of resting sites for small migratory birds. The Tree's removal would eliminate its contributions to wildlife habitat and deprive the Respondents of the accompanying experiences.</P1>
<P1>(f) <EM>Stormwater Reduction</EM>:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>. at p. 7, RAR, p. 56</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Mature urban trees can protect and improve water quality and help to reduce stormwater runoff, erosion and flooding. The Maple may contribute to a reduced incidence of basement flooding on adjacent properties, and the Tree's removal may increase the frequency and/or severity of such flooding events. The van Wassenaer Report references the parties' neighbour, Ms. Lang, who advises that the Maple's &ldquo;massive root system is beneficial in soaking up rain and melting snow and I fear the removal of this very large and established healthy tree could cause more flooding issues on my property.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Lang Letter, MacDougall Affidavit, Exhibit H, RAR, p. 35.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(g) <EM>Decline of Other Trees</EM>:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Van Wassenaer Report at p. 7, RAR, p. 56.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Maple is one of three large trees on the property at [location omitted] [location omitted] The other two are beech trees, which are infected by a terminal disease known as Beech bark disease and likely to require removal within five years. The eventual loss of those trees makes the retention of the Maple and the benefits that it provides even more important to [location omitted] and the Respondents.</P1></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>(iii)</EM></N><TI><EM>The Applicants Planned their Renovation Without Regard for the Maple and the Respondents' Rights</EM></TI>
<P>19. In and around April 2017, the Applicants advised the Respondents of their proposed renovation of [location omitted]. It became apparent from these conversations that the destruction and removal of the Maple was a part of the Applicants' plans. The Respondents made it clear from the outset that they would not consent to the Maple's removal because it was too important to them and contributed significantly to the enjoyment of their property.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MacDougall Affidavit at para. 12, RAR, p. 4.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>20. Although the Applicants promised to share their construction plans as they developed, the Applicants ignored the Respondents' requests for updates throughout the summer and fall of 2 017. When Mr. Allen finally did share the particulars of the plans at a mid-December 2017 meeting, he delivered them in the form of a finished set of architectural drawings which envisioned the Maple's destruction.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MacDougall Affidavit at paras. 13-14, RAR, p. 4.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>21. Ms. MacDougall sent the Applicants an email shortly thereafter, on December 23, 2017. In her message, Ms. MacDougall reiterated the importance of the Maple to her family while emphasizing that she and Mr. Scott had no objection to a construction project that did not involve removal of the tree:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email from Meghan MacDougall to Susan Allen dated December 23, 2018, Allen Affidavit, Exhibit F, AR, pp. 56-57 (Emphasis added).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>Drew, thanks for coming over and sharing the plans with us. It was great to see how you want to improve your house. When you showed us the plans, you made it clear that it was your intention to have the tree removed. <UNDER>As you know, this is something that we are against as the tree provides some vital shade for our house and garden and is one of the reasons why we enjoy our house so much in the summer. It adds considerable value to the enjoyment of our property and is one of the reasons we chose this neighbourhood.</UNDER> In addition, we have had two arborists confirm that the tree is healthy...</P>
<P>Whilst we do want to be good neighbours, this is something we are not willing to negotiate on and want to state quite clearly that we do not give you permission to cut down the tree. <UNDER>We are not against you developing or renovating your house at all we just hope that you and your architect can find a solution and design that does not require the removal of the tree.</UNDER></P>
<P>Happy to discuss this further if you like.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>22. The Applicants did not respond to Ms. MacDougall's overture or otherwise consult with the Respondents about the proposed renovation. The Respondents' subsequent attempts to discuss the matter with the Applicants also went unanswered.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See e.g., Email from Nigel Scott to Drew Allen and Sue Allen, April 10, 20 18, MacDougall Affidavit, Exhibit E, RAR, p. 24.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>23. In early 2018, the Respondents participated in a mediation involving the Applicants and their architect, Tom Spragge. Although the Respondents approached the mediation in good faith, it was not successful.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MacDougall Affidavit at para. 24, RAR, p. 6.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>24. As is required for an application for a permit to injure or destroy a tree, the Applicants included a replanting plan. The plan proposed by the Applicants and their architect does not consider the Respondents or compensate for the loss of the Maple. Mr. van Wassenauer states that the so-called replacement trees proposed in the replanting plan will provide little to no benefit to [location omitted] because they are located far from the Respondents' property and will take decades to mature into trees that can provide a canopy comparable to what the Maple presently provides.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Van Wassenaer Report at p. 12, RAR, p. 61.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>(iv)</EM></N><TI><EM>The &ldquo;Approvals&rdquo; Obtained by the Applicants Are Irrelevant to this Application</EM></TI>
<P>25. In January 2018, a month after Ms. MacDougall's email, the Applicants sought and obtained certain minor variances from the Committee of Adjustment. In June 2018 they obtained building permits from Toronto Urban Forestry and the City of Toronto Building Department. These administrative decisions are necessary to comply with the City of Toronto by-laws, but do not in any way give the Applicants permission to destroy the Maple.</P>
<BLOCK5><N><EM>1</EM>.</N><TI><EM>The Committee of Adjustment Did not Consider the Maple</EM></TI>
<P>26. The Applicants attended at the Committee of Adjustment to obtain certain minor variances as a prerequisite for the proposed renovation. The variances requested were for increases in the maximum allowable (i) floorspace, (ii) building length, (iii) gross floor area, and (iv) side lot setback.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Notice of Decision dated January 30, 2018, Allen Affidavit, Exhibit H, AR, p. 68.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Committee did not specifically consider issues relating to the Maple. (Nor does the Committee <EM>ever</EM> deal with property disputes as between neighbours.)</P>
<P>27. Prior to retaining counsel, the Respondents did make written representations to the Committee and attended a January 24, 2018 meeting regarding the Applicants' request.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email from Meg Scott to Sylvia Mullaste, Allen Affidavit, Exhibit G, AR, p. 59; MacDougall Affidavit at para. 22, RAR, p. 6</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> At that hearing, the Respondents learned that the Committee of Adjustment was not the proper forum in which to adjudicate the protection of the Maple.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>MacDougall Affidavit at paras 22-23, RAR, p. 6.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Specifically, the panel advised that it did not have jurisdiction to consider the Maple, but only the minor variances requested by the Applicants. As such, the Respondents did not appeal when the Committee ultimately approved the Applicants' request. Mr. Allen acknowledged on cross-examination that the Committee of Adjustment lacks the jurisdiction to determine what is or is not a boundary tree and does not adjudicate property disputes between neighbours.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Allen Transcript, P. 32, QQ. 293-294, Transcript Brief, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>28. At paragraph 37 of his affidavit, Mr. Allen comments that the Moore Park Residents Association did not oppose the Applicants' request to the Committee of Adjustment. This evidence is misleading. In a letter dated November 19, 2018, the Director of the Association states that the Association may have intervened had the Applicants disclosed that the proposed renovation contemplated the Maple's destruction. He writes that the Applicants' plan to destroy the Maple is anathema to the Moore Park Residents Association's commitment to preserving the canopy of trees that define the neighbourhood:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Gawen Letter, MacDougall Affidavit, Exhibit G, RAR, p. 32 (Emphasis added).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>We again reviewed the plans and concluded that the variances were indeed &ldquo;minor&rdquo; in nature and so we decided not to intervene. <UNDER>At that time we had no idea that there was a tree issue and that construction would involve the destruction of a beautiful mature tree on the Boundary with #89. If we had been aware of this, we most likely would have opposed the application because we want to preserve the canopy of trees for which Moore Park is well known.</UNDER> Such trees provide shade for our houses in the summer and, particularly in this area where groundwater is a problem, suck up large amounts of water to help reduce flooding.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>29. Another neighbour, Michael Bartouche, states that he did not support the Applicants' request to the Committee of Adjustment specifically because he objected to the removal of the Maple.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Bertouche Letter, MacDougall Affidavit, Exhibit I, RAR, p. 37.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He continues, &ldquo;The [Applicants] were made aware that I was not supportive of this renovation as I believe the beauty of Moore Park and the tree canopy is special and valuable to the community and needs to be preserved. At this point, [Mr. Allen] said my support wasn't required anymore anyway.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>..</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N><EM>2</EM>.</N><TI><EM>A Permit Is Necessary but not Sufficient To Remove the Maple</EM></TI>
<P>30. The Applicants have obtained certain permits from Toronto Urban Forestry and the City of Toronto Building Department as a prerequisite to the proposed renovation. There is no dispute that the Applicants have obtained a permit to injure a tree. Those permits, however, do not authorize the destruction of the Maple without the Respondents' consent.</P>
<P>31. The Applicants attach significant weight to the permit to destroy a tree. Indeed, Toronto Urban Forestry notified the Applicants of its decision to issue a permit in a March 22, 2018 notification letter (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Notification Letter</BOLD>&rdquo;).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Letter of Lisa Carson dated March 22, 2018 (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Notification Letter</BOLD>&rdquo;), Allen Affidavit, Exhibit O, AR, p. 98</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Notification Letter expressly states that it does not limit the rights of adjoining property owners or authorize the destruction of a tree. It explains that it is only a release of the Applicants' obligations under the Toronto city by-laws, but does not release them of their legal obligations to their neighbours:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Notification Letter, Allen Affidavit, Exhibit O, AR, p. 98.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>We wish to emphasize that the issuance of a permit to remove the above noted tree does not supersede any civil or common law property rights. The permit is only an acknowledgment that the proposed removal, if carried out in accordance wit the terms and conditions of the permit, will not constitute a violation of the Private Tree By-Law. <UNDER>The permit does not determine ownership and does not authorize you as the applicant to encroach upon or enter another's private property or to remove a tree owned by another without their consent.</UNDER> It is your responsibility as the applicant to resolve any ownership issue or other property disputes.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>32. Similarly, the June 20, 2018 letters accompanying the Applicants' building permits confirm that the proposed renovation complies with city by-laws and do not even mention the Maple.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Building Permits 18 157345 PLB 00 PS and 18 157345 PLB 00 PS, Allen Affidavit, Exhibit R and S, AR, pp. 108 and 113.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The building permits are entirely irrelevant to the issues on this Application.</P></BLOCK5>
<BLOCK5><N><EM>3</EM>.</N><TI><EM>The Applicants' Speculation About the Permit Process Is Unfounded</EM></TI>
<P>33. At paragraph 77 of their factum, the Applicants assert that Toronto Urban Forestry undertook certain due diligence prior to issuing the permit. These assertions are entirely speculative, and the Applicants have not provided any evidence as to Toronto Urban Forestry's ordinary practice in processing permit applications or what municipal employees did in this particular case. Despite relying on the Toronto Strategic Forest Management Plan,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Applicants' Factum at para. 77.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the Applicants have not included that plan in the record,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>At Tab 2D of the Transcript Brief, the Applicants include a one-page overview of the Toronto Strategic Forest Management Plan as Exhibit 4 for identification on the cross-examination of Mr. van Wassenaer. This summary document contains no detail and is not the plan itself. See van Wassenaer Transcript, P. 17, Q. 85, Transcript Brief, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> identified what provisions of the Plan they rely upon, or explained how it is taken into account in permit applications.</P>
<P>34. At paragraphs 39-40 of their factum, the Applicants make a number of assertions regarding the impartiality of Mr. van Wassenaer's evidence as to the practices of Toronto Urban Forestry. The Applicants charge that Mr. van Wassenaer violated his Acknowledgement of Expert's Duty<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Acknowledgment of Expert's Duty sworn January 8, 2019, Wassenaer Affidavit, Exhibit A, RAR, p. 45.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> for refusing to give speculative answers outside his personal knowledge and expertise.</P>
<P>35. More specifically, the Applicants criticize Mr. van Wassenaer for declining to agree that Toronto Urban Forestry took into account, among other things, shade, energy savings, and air quality when assessing the Maple. Mr. van Wassenaer had no factual basis to agree with the inferences put to him by counsel. He was not involved in the permit-issuance process. Moreover, the terms &ldquo;shade&rdquo;, &ldquo;energy savings&rdquo;, and &ldquo;air quality&rdquo; do not appear in either the Toronto Tree Protection Policy (which formed the basis of counsel's questions)<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See van Wassenaer Transcript, PP. 34&ndash;44, QQ. 169&ndash;201, Transcript Brief, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> or the Notification Letter. Mr. van Wassenaer's evidence was that in his experience Toronto Urban Forestry deals with a significant volume of applications and does not always follow its own policies.</P>
<P>36. As the excerpt below demonstrates, Mr. van Wassenaer acted fairly, impartially, and answered questions within his personal knowledge and expertise:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Van Wassenaer Transcript, PP. 30&ndash;32, QQ 157&ndash;160, Transcript Brief, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>Q. All right. And the Urban Forestry would make an assessment of the impact of the tree on air quality?</P>
<P>A. They may but it's, you know, given the number of applications they process and the number of trees that they look at, they might do that, but I think it would be unlikely they are assessing each and every one of these attributes. I think they are...these are attributes that they would generally consider. I find it unlikely that they perform an analysis of each application for each of these attributes.</P>
<P>Q. Sir, I take it from your answer that you are not 100% confident, notwithstanding that you claim expertise in urban forestry, that you are aware of what the process of what the City of Toronto Urban Forestry goes through when assessing a tree destruction permit application.</P>
<P>A. I'm quite aware of the policy and the procedure that is in print and in paper. I'm also, from a practical perspective, have experienced that all of that policy is not always applied. That is my professional experience working in the City of Toronto.</P>
<P>Q. I take it, sir, with respect to the consideration of the Allens' tree destruction permit you don't know whether the policy was or was not followed.</P>
<P>A. I don't, no. I do not know who the planner was in this case. I do not know what material they chose to look at and how extensive a review they did of that material. Unfortunately it is one of the issues that we experience a variability in how these applications are dealt with over time and across individuals.</P>
<P>Q. Fair enough, sir. So then you will agree with me then in the absence of evidence that the individual who reviewed the application didn't follow the policy, then the policy was followed.</P>
<P>A. I'm not sure I can agree with that statement because I simply just don't know.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>37. These answers are perfectly reasonable and reflect an expert who has chosen to stay within the bounds of his knowledge and expertise rather than accept counsel's invitation to speculate about the practice of an agency for whom he does not work. There is no evidence about Toronto Urban Forestry's general or specific practice regarding a permit issuance. Mr. van Wassanaer was not partial. He simply refused to give the answer that the Applicants wanted.</P></BLOCK5></BLOCK4></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>C.</N><TI>The Applicants Can Significantly Improve their Property without Destroying the Maple</TI>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>(i)</EM></N><TI><EM>Most of the Proposed Renovation Can Happen while Leaving the Tree Alone</EM></TI>
<P>38. It is possible to significantly improve the Applicants' home with the Maple intact.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Allen Transcript at P. 27, Q 180, Transcript Brief, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Applicants have raised three children, now teenagers, in their 2400-square-foot Moore Park home. Since acquiring the property in 2001, they have renovated their bathrooms and master bedroom, and updated the home's electrical, flooring, and external doors and windows.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Allen Affidavit at para. 11, AR, p. 13; Allen Transcript, PP. 25&ndash;27, QQ. 165&ndash;179, Transcript Brief, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> They were able to complete those renovations without harming any trees.</P>
<P>39. At paragraphs 14 through 34 of his Affidavit, Mr. Allen lists a number of &ldquo;practical issues&rdquo;&mdash;problems with their current home&mdash;that the Applicants wish to remedy with the proposed renovation. He describes these problems that must be addressed to &ldquo;bring the house up to current safety, wellness and comfort standards.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Allen Affidavit para. 19, AR, p. 15.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> These practical issues consist of: (i) an inconsistent heating system and air conditioning, (ii) lack of proper insulation, (iii) periodic flooding, and (iv) the presence of knob and tube wiring.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>. at paras. 14 through 34, AR, pp. 14&ndash;17; Allen Transcript, PP 28&ndash;30, QQ 181&ndash;196, Transcript Brief, Tab 1</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>40. Mr. Allen conceded on cross-examination that the Applicants can fix <EM>all</EM> of these problems without harming the Maple.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Allen Transcript, PP. 28&ndash;30, QQ. 183-184, QQ 181&ndash;195, Transcript Brief, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Maple is no impediment to replacing the heating, insulation and wiring in the existing structure, nor does it prevent the Applicants from dealing with a purported flooding issue.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>(ii)</EM></N><TI><EM>The Respondents Can Expand their Home while Retaining the Maple</EM></TI>
<P>41. The only potential constraint that the Maple imposes on the proposed renovation relates to the manner and extent to which the Applicants can increase the square footage of their home. The proposed renovation contemplates replacing the Applicants' existing addition with a larger one that will expand size of their home by over 50%, from 2400 to 3700 square feet.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Allen Affidavit at para. 31, AR, p. 17.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Applicants' architectural plan calls for moving the basement foundation walls into the yard of [location omitted] and near the boundary of [location omitted], which is where the Maple's roots are located.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Van Wassenaer Report at p. 10, RAR, p. 59.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>42. According to Mr. van Wassenaer, expanding the foundation of [location omitted] in this manner will encroach deep into the Maple's Tree Protection Zone (&ldquo;<BOLD>TPZ</BOLD>&rdquo;) and kill the tree.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Van Wassenaer Transcript, P. 56, QQ 270&ndash;272, Transcript Brief, Tab 2a.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> A TPZ is a fenced area surrounding a tree that protects both its trunk and the root system below ground from construction impacts.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Van Wassenaer Report at p. 8, RAR, p. 57.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> As set out in the <EM>Toronto Tree Protection Policy and Specifications for Constructions Near Trees</EM> (2016) (the &ldquo;<BOLD>Tree Protection Policy</BOLD>&rdquo;),<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Toronto Tree Protection Policy and Specifications for Constructions Near Trees</EM> (2016), Van Wassenaer Report, Appendix 2, RAR, pp. 71-72.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> construction and excavation are generally prohibited in a TPZ. Practically speaking, however, it is impossible to completely prohibit construction in the TPZ of all urban trees. For instance, the Applicants' existing addition already encroaches on the Maple's TPZ.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Van Wassenaer Report, Appendix 1, Figure 3, RAR, p. 64.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>43. Mr. van Wassenaer's opinion is not that the Applicants are barred entirely from building in the TPZ. Rather, his evidence is that a tree-sensitive design is required, such that the architects and planners must consider reducing excavation or fill in the area between the Tree and the footprint of the existing addition.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Van Wassenaer Transcript, Q. 55, Q 266, Transcript Brief, Tab 2a.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>44. The van Wassenaer Report explains that it is the Applicants' insistence on a fully excavated basement that renders the proposed renovation incompatible with the Maple. Relying on his experience in formulating protection measures around trees in order to facilitate construction projects,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>., PP 50-51, QQ. 237-238, Transcript Brief, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> he maintains that there &ldquo;are many different design opportunities that would allow for a significant addition to built [location omitted] while respecting the preservation requirements of [the Maple].&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Van Wassenaer Report at p. 11, RAR, p. 60.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> According to Mr. van Wassenaer, what is essential is that the below ground portion of the current design be reduced and proper tree preservation protocols implemented during construction:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>., at pp. 10-11, RAR, pp. 59-60.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>...[The] current site design for the renovations at [location omitted] precludes the provision of the required TPZ for [the Maple] because of the size and location of the rear addition. The exterior wall of the proposed addition would be within 1m of the base of [the Maple] and the over-dig excavation required to build the wall and its foundations would encroach even further into the minimum TPZ of [the Maple], Building the proposed one-story addition will effectively remove a large portion of the root system including the structural roots of the tree.</P>
<P>The current design requires the removal of [the Maple]. However, if the preservation requirements for [the Maple] were properly taken into account in the design process, there may still be opportunities for the development of an addition to the existing house. However, I could only evaluate the specific impacts to [the Maple] if an alternate design and the accompanying tree preservation plans were available. I am not aware of any such alternative designs.</P>
<P>At a minimum however, a successful alternative design would require a reduction in the extent of the below-ground renovation, thereby reducing the loss of roots within the TPZ of [the Maple]. The proposed one-storey addition currently provides a full basement. If the below-ground portion of the current design were reduced and proper tree preservation protocols were implemented during the construction of the addition, there should be ways to preserve [the Maple] (subject to the specific details of the alternate design). A viable alternative should allow for a substantial portion of the proposed addition to be constructed.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>45. Without commenting on what precise design opportunities are available, Mr. van Wassenaer concludes that it is at least possible to both retain the Maple and improve upon the Applicants' existing addition. An arborist such as Mr. van Wassenaer could have assisted the Applicants' architects in designing such tree-sensitive plans.</P>
<P>46. It is not unreasonable to limit the scope of the Applicants' renovation to something slightly under 50% of its present size. The Applicants can still build a substantial addition. They can build on the existing footprint; they can build an addition that is slightly smaller than the present design and which employs a proper Tree Protection Plan; or they can build a large addition that expands only to the south, away from [location omitted]and the Maple. There may be also more sophisticated solutions that require technical expertise. For instance, Mr. van Wassenaer testified on cross-examination that there are different kinds of foundations that do not require excavation, such as a foundation on piers with a grade beam.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Wassenear Transcript, PP. 55-56, QQ. 268-269, Transcript Brief, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>47. This Application likely would have been avoided if the Applicants had explored reasonable, viable alternatives.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;STATEMENT OF ISSUES, LAW &amp; AUTHORITIES</TI>
<P>48. The Respondents' position on the issues raised in this Application are as follows:
<P1>(a) The Maple is a boundary tree and the common property of the parties. The Applicants therefore cannot destroy it without the Respondents' consent.</P1>
<P1>(b) The Maple is not a nuisance within the meaning of the law. Consequently, the Applicants cannot dispense with the requirement to obtain the Respondents' consent to destroy the tree.</P1></P>
<BLOCK3><N>A.</N><TI>The Applicants Require the Consent of the Respondents Because the Maple Is a Boundary Tree</TI>
<P>49. The Applicants concede that the Maple is a boundary tree within the meaning of the <EM>Forestry Act</EM> and at common law and that it is therefore the common property of the parties.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Allen Transcript, PP. 15&ndash;17, QQ. 93&ndash;102, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>50. Where there is common ownership of a tree, consent of all the owners is required for removal or maintenance.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Hartley v. Cunningham</SOC><CITE>2013 ONSC 2929</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Hartley SCJ</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;), aff'd 2013 ONCA 759 (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Hartley OCA</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;), Respondents Book of Authorities (&ldquo;<BOLD>RBOA</BOLD>&rdquo;), Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Section 10(2) of the <EM>Forestry Act</EM> prescribes that &ldquo;every tree whose trunk is growing on the boundary between adjoining lands is the common property of the owners of the adjoining lands.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Forestry Act</EM>, s. 10(2).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Section 10(3) of the Act creates an offence for any person who injures and destroys such a tree without the consent of the landowners.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>, s. 10(3).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>51. In <CASEREF><SOC>Hartley v. Cunningham</SOC></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Hartley (OCA)</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;), the Ontario Court of Appeal confirmed that a tree will be deemed a boundary tree if any part of its trunk&mdash;defined as the growth between its roots and branches&mdash;straddles the property line in question.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hartley (OCA) at paras. 3-4, RBOA, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The proportion of the tree on either side of the boundary is irrelevant to a determination of the shared rights between adjacent property owners.</P>
<P>52. Issuance of a permit does not relieve a party from the obligation to obtain consent to destroy a boundary tree. In <CASEREF><SOC>Scheuermann v. Gross</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Scheuermann v. Gross</SOC><CITE>2017 ONCJ 722</CITE><PARANUM>4, 137, 145, 147, 160</PARANUM></CASEREF> RBOA, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the accused obtained a Confirmation of Exemption from the City of Toronto. The Confirmation of Exemption permitted the accused to remove a boundary tree, a Norway maple, without a permit on the basis that it was a hazard but advised that it remained his responsibility to resolve any ownership issues. Nevertheless, the accused removed the tree without his neighbours' consent. He was convicted of an offence under section 10(3) of the <EM>Forestry Act</EM> despite the Confirmation of Exemption.</P>
<P>53. The Applicants rely on <CASEREF><SOC>Centrum Land Corporation v. Institute of Chartered Accountants of Ontario</SOC></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Centrum</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;), a decision decided under now-repealed legislation. In <EM>Centrum</EM>, the High Court concluded that &ldquo;there are no restrictions to the right of a landowner to cut down trees growing on the boundary line, apart from the restrictions that exists a common law, if any.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Centrum Land Corporation v. Institute of Chartered Accountants of Ontario et al</SOC></CASEREF>. (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Centrum</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;), 1988, CarswellOnt 193 (Ont. H.C.) at para. 18, Applicants' Book of Authorities (&ldquo;<BOLD>ABOA</BOLD>&rdquo;), Tab 6.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> <EM>Centrum</EM>, however, is a 30-year-old case decided pursuant to the now-repealed <EM>Trees Act</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>R.S.O., 1980, c. 510.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Unlike the current operative statute, the <EM>Forestry Act</EM>, the <EM>Trees Act</EM> does not expressly deem boundary trees to be common property. The decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Hartley v. Cunningham</SOC></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Hartley (SCJ)</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;) confirmed that the boundary tree provisions in the <EM>Forestry Act</EM> had overtaken the <EM>Trees Act</EM>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hartley SCJ at paras. 17&ndash;20, RBOA, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><N>B.</N><TI>The Maple Is not a Nuisance</TI>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>(i)</EM></N><TI><EM>Nuisance Requires Interference that Is Both Substantial and Unreasonable</EM></TI>
<P>54. The Applicants assert that although the Respondents have a property right in the Maple, they may dispense with obtaining the Respondents' consent because the Tree is a nuisance.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>For this proposition, the Applicants rely on <CASEREF><SOC>Freedman v. Cooper</SOC><CITE>2015 CarswellOnt 2875</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, ABOA, Tab 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> A nuisance is an unreasonable interference with the use and enjoyment of land. It must be &ldquo;intolerable to an ordinary person&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>St. Lawrence Cement Inc. v. Barrette</SOC><CITE>[2008] 3 S.C.R. 392</CITE><PARANUM>77</PARANUM></CASEREF>, RBOA, Tab 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>55. In <CASEREF><SOC>Antrim Truck Centre Ltd. v. Ontario (Ministry of Transportation)</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Antrim Truck Centre Ltd, v. Ontario (Transportation)</SOC></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Antrim</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;), [2013] 1 S.C.R. 594, RBOA, Tab 4.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the Supreme Court of Canada explained that to support a claim in private nuisance, the interference with the owner's use or enjoyment of land must be both substantial and unreasonable. A substantial inference with property is one that is non-trivial. Reasonableness is not considered unless and until the threshold of substantial interference is met. It is concerned with whether the non-trivial interference is unreasonable in all the circumstances.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>(ii)</EM></N><TI><EM>The Maple Does not Interfere with the Applicants' Land</EM></TI>
<P>56. The continued existence of the Maple does not substantially interfere with the Applicants or their property. The Tree does not prevent the Applicants from renovating their bedrooms and bathrooms, replacing their insulation, wiring, heating and cooling systems, or addressing any purported flooding. It does not prevent them from improving their basement or expanding the square footage of their home. To the extent that the Maple affects the Applicants, it requires them to deviate somewhat from their current architectural plans by reducing the size or altering the dimensions of their walkout basement.</P>
<P>57. The law of nuisance is defined by the standard of an ordinary, reasonable person. The purported nuisance must amount to more than a slight annoyance or trifling interference.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Antrim</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 22, RBOA, Tab 4.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> It must be an inconvenience that materially interferes with ordinary comfort &ldquo;as defined according to standards held by those of plain and sober tastes.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>..</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Claims based &ldquo;on the prompting of excessive &lsquo;delicacy and fastidiousness&rsquo;&rdquo; are not actionable.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>58. This is not a case where the purported nuisance poses a danger to person or property. The Maple tree is by <EM>all</EM> accounts healthy and does not pose a hazard to either [location omitted]<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Van Wassenaer Report at p. 4, RAR, p. 53; Vandermeij Report, AR p. 28.; Arborist Report of Mark Procunier dated December 20, 2017, Allen Affidavit, Exhibit K, AR p. 79; Allen Transcript, P. 22, Q. 140, Transcript Brief, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Mr. Allen conceded that all of the professionals who had examined the Maple acknowledged that it was healthy and, if undisturbed, would live for many more years.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Allen Transcript, PP. 22&ndash;24; QQ 140&ndash;154, Transcript Brief, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Those professionals also emphasized that the Maple posed no danger to anyone.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> While absence of danger is not determinative of nuisance, it is a good indicator of a lack of substantial interference.</P>
<P>59. This case is unlike <CASEREF><SOC>Davis v. Sutton</SOC></CASEREF>, on which the Applicants rely. In that case, the plaintiff sued the defendant after he engaged in self-help by removing certain boundary trees. The court found the trees to have been a nuisance in the circumstances because they prevented the defendants from building a fence for the express purpose of ensuring the safety of their six -year old child with special needs.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Davis v. Sutton</SOC><CITE>2017 CarswellOnt 5533</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. Div. Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras. 15, 45 ABOA Tab 3</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There was no reasonable alternative to the destruction of the trees.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>. at para. 17, ABOA, Tab 3.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>60. This Application does not involve danger, the safety and security of a child, or any such serious concern. The Applicants simply want to increase the size of their already large home by 50%. They assert that their &ldquo;needs&rdquo; cannot be reasonably accommodated with the Maple in place. But when pressed on cross-examination, it became clear that the Applicants' &ldquo;needs&rdquo; amounted to no more than the desires of the well-to-do: more storage space, more entertainment space and more bedrooms.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>On cross-examination Mr. Allen swore that his family's home had three bedrooms. This evidence must be evaluated in the context of a Municipal Property Assessment Corporation printout produced by counsel for the Applicants' one week later, on Ms. MacDougall's cross-examination. That document indicates that[location omitted]it is in fact a four-bedroom home. Allen Transcript, P. 24; QQ 229&ndash;233, Transcript Brief, Tab 1; MacDougall Transcript, P. 24, QQ. 130-131, Transcript Brief, Tab 3; MCAP Print-Out, MacDougall Transcript, Exhibit 1, Transcript Brief, Tab 3A.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Applicants may well wish to have more space in their home while their teenaged children remain there, but a modest constraint on their ability to do so to accommodate their neighbours' property rights does not amount a material interference on a standard of plain and sober tastes. Mr. Allen's own words make clear that it is a sense of entitlement, not nuisance, that has created this impasse:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Allen Transcript, PP. 33&ndash;36, QQ 217, 223&ndash;226; 237&ndash;241; 245, Transcript Brief, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>Q. Now you write in your affidavit...you swear in your affidavit &ldquo;If the tree is not removed then no addition to the house can be reasonably accomplished that would accommodate our needs&rdquo;. That is at paragraph 30 of your affidavit, page 17 of the record.</P>
<P>A. Yes.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>Q. What are those needs?</P>
<P>A. We require more space because there is not sufficient space in the house as it currently exists to allow us to do what we want to do with the house.</P>
<P>Q. What do you want to be able to do?</P>
<P>A. We want to be able to enjoy the house.</P>
<P>Q. By doing what?</P>
<P>A. By making it bigger.</P>
<P>Q. Why?</P>
<P>A. Because we don't have sufficient room for our family as it currently stands.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>Q. You mentioned you want an additional room so your kids can have separate rooms, and more storage space and activity space?</P>
<P>A. Yes, I think that summarizes it.</P>
<P>Q. These to me sound more like desires than needs.</P>
<P>A. No.</P>
<P>Q. These are needs?</P>
<P>A. They are.</P>
<P>Q. You are suffering presently?</P>
<P>A. Relatively speaking, yes.</P>
<P>Q. Relative to whom, sir?</P>
<P>A. Third world nations.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>Q. Your position is you are suffering relative to third world nations?</P>
<P>A. I may have exaggerated a bit there.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>61. Further and in any event, the Applicants have not introduced evidence capable of supporting their argument that their desire to expand their home requires the destruction of the Maple. The Applicants bear the burden to prove not only interference with their property but that the interference is substantial.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Antrim</EM>, at para. 28, RBOA, Tab 4.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> They have not discharged their onus to prove, as they submit, that there is no alternative to the designs prepared by their architect.</P>
<P>62. The van Wassenaer Report, which is uncontradicted, concludes that the Applicants can reconfigure their designs to obtain the desired expansion while still preserving the Maple. The Applicants have tendered no evidence to rebut Mr. van Wassenaer's expert opinion. Indeed, their case relies on a vague and self-serving statement from Mr. Allen that &ldquo;we tried to come up with building plans that would meet our needs while preserving the Tree, if at all reasonably possible.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Allen Affidavit at para. 30, AR, p. 30.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There is no evidence from Mr. Spragge himself to support the submission he &ldquo;was not able to come up with a possible and reasonable plan which would allow the Applicants to preserve the tree.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Applicants' Factum at para. 18.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Further, on cross-examination, Mr. Allen conceded that the Applicants never even asked their architect to <EM>try</EM> to come up with designs that accommodated the Tree, nor did the Applicants ask their architect to re-examine the question after reviewing Mr. van Wassanaer's Report, which unequivocally states that building an addition while preserving the Tree is possible.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Allen Transcript, PP. 38-39, QQ 217, 223&ndash;226; 237&ndash;241; 245, Transcript Brief, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>63. Bizarrely, at paragraphs 41 through 46 and 67 of their factum, the Applicants criticize the Respondents and Mr. van Wassenaer for not proposing detailed alternative plans to the proposed renovation. The Applicants thus attempt to invert the evidentiary burden: the onus is on them to show that there is no reasonable alternative to the proposed renovation. It is not for the Respondents to commission architects, engineers, and arborists to devise plans for the Applicants' home renovation.</P>
<P>64. The truth is that that the Applicants do have alternatives available to them, but they are inflexible. The Applicants have known since April 2017 of the importance of the Maple to the Respondents. They do not care. Throughout, the Applicants have refused to engage or meaningfully explore a compromise that takes into account their shared property. As became apparent during Mr. Allen's cross-examination, the Applicants are uninterested in anything but the design of their choice and are indifferent to the property rights and concerns of their neighbours:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>., P. 32, 38-39, Q 216; QQ 267&ndash;273, Transcript Brief, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>Q. So you never instructed your architect to put together a set of architectural drawings that would preserve the tree?</P>
<P>A. No.</P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P>Q. The truth is you are not interested in trying to accommodate your neighbours' property rights, correct?</P>
<P>A. No.</P>
<P>Q. You don't think a pesky tree should be permitted to get in the way of your renovation.</P>
<P>A. No.</P>
<P>Q. You didn't want to have to build a lopsided renovation. Right? That's what is at the root of this, correct?</P>
<P>A. Yes.</P>
<P>Q. I'm right in saying that?</P>
<P>A. Yes.</P>
<P>Q. It is not that the tree couldn't be accommodated, it is that you didn't want to accommodate it, correct?</P>
<P>A. It was not reasonably possible.</P>
<P>Q. Well, you could have built an addition, but it wouldn't have been this addition, correct?</P>
<P>A. Correct.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>65. It appears that the Applicants inflexibility is profit-driven. Mr. Allen revealed on cross-examination that the Applicants are exploring the possibility of selling their house and that the purpose of the proposed renovation is to increase the sale price:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Allen Transcript, P. 37 QQ. 256&ndash;259, Transcript Brief, Tab 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>Q. You are exploring the sale of your home, correct?</P>
<P>A. We are.</P>
<P>Q. Indeed you want to implement these renovations to increase the sale price of your home, correct?</P>
<P>A. Yes.</P>
<P>Q. You want to destroy the tree to increase your property's value?</P>
<P>A. Yes.</P>
<P>Q. You want to destroy your neighbours' property to increase the value of your own, correct?</P>
<P>A. Yes.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>66. In <CASEREF><SOC>Yates v. Fedirchuk</SOC></CASEREF>, Justice Annis commented that &ldquo;appropriate neighbourhood relations is what the law of nuisance is all about.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Yates v. Fedirchuk</SOC><CITE>2011 ONSC 5549</CITE></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Yates</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;) at para. 6, RBOA, Tab 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Indeed, it is a vehicle for balancing the competing rights of landowners, not to subordinate the interests of one party below that of another.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Pugliese v. Canada (National Capital Commission)</SOC></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Pugliese</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;) (1977), 17 O.R. (2d) 129, varied on another point [1979] 2 S.C.R. 104, RBOA, Tab 6.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The law of nuisance protects against noxious and unreasonable inconveniences. It is not a tool for one landowner to enhance the value of their own property at the expense of their neighbour's.</P></BLOCK4>
<BLOCK4><N><EM>(iii)</EM></N><TI><EM>Any Interference Caused by Maple Is Reasonable</EM></TI>
<P>67. This Court should not engage in a reasonableness analysis unless it finds the Maple to be a substantial interference with [location omitted]. Regardless, any interference caused by Maple is reasonable in the circumstances.</P>
<P>68. The reasonableness of an interference is assessed on the objective standard of a reasonable person set in the context of the general uses found in the area. In <CASEREF><SOC>Pugliese v. Canada (National Capital Commission)</SOC></CASEREF>, the Ontario Court of Appeal explained:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid</EM>..</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>In determining whether a nuisance exists, it is not sufficient to ask whether an occupier has made a reasonable use of his own property. One must ask whether his conduct is reasonable considering the fact that he has a neighbour. As Lord Wright pointed out in <CASEREF><SOC>Sedleigh-Denfield v. O'Callaghan</SOC><CITE>[19401 A.C. 880</CITE><PAGENUM>at 903</PAGENUM><CORRELAT><CITE>[1940] 3 All E.R. 349</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>A balance has to be maintained between the right of the occupier to do what he likes with his own, and the right of his neighbour not to be interfered with. It is impossible to give any precise or universal formula, but it may broadly be said that a useful test is perhaps what is reasonable according to the ordinary usages of mankind living in society, or more correctly in a particular society.</P></QUOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>69. In <EM>Yates</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> this Court identified five factors to consider in determining whether there has been an unreasonable interference with a use and enjoyment of land: (i) the type of severity of harm, (ii) the character of the locale, (iii) whether the complainants or their property are abnormally sensitive, and (iv) the utility of the impugned conduct.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Yates</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> at paras. 32-33, RBOA, Tab 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>70. All of the foregoing factors favour the Respondents:
<P1>(a) <EM>Severity of Harm</EM>: The potential harm to the Applicants is modest. At most, the Maple poses a limit to the size of their addition and in particular their ability to have a fully excavated basement. Even these restrictions could be mitigated with an alternative, tree-sensitive design.</P1>
<P1>(b) <EM>Character of the Locale</EM>: As underscored by the letters from Mr. Gawen, Ms. Lang, and Mr. Bartouche, the Moore Park neighbourhood is renowned for its trees and was a primary reason that the Respondents chose to live in the neighbourhood. Moore Park's canopy undoubtedly contributes value to the neighbourhood's properties, including[location omitted]</P1>
<P1>(c) <EM>Abnormal Sensitivity</EM>: The Applicants have an idiosyncratic, entitled conception of what &ldquo;they require to meet the needs of their family&rdquo; that is unlikely to be shared by an ordinary person of plain and sober tastes.</P1>
<P1>(d) <EM>Utility</EM>: The aesthetic and material benefits of the Maple, including those relating to animal habitat, air quality, and stormwater reduction, accrue not only to the Applicants but also their neighbours. The Tree Protection Policy underscores the importance of the urban trees more generally: &ldquo;Maintenance, growth, and enhancement of the urban forest are important goals of the City of Toronto.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Toronto Tree Protection Policy, p. 3, van Wassenaer Report, Appendix 2, RAR, p. 68.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>71. A court must have particular regard to the character of the neighbourhood in determining the reasonableness of an interference with the use and enjoyment of land.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Gallant v. Dugard</SOC><CITE>2016 ONSC 7319</CITE><PARANUM>16-17</PARANUM></CASEREF>, RBOA, Tab 7.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> What may be reasonable in one area may be unreasonable in another. For example, there will be greater tolerance in a rural area for agricultural sights, sounds, and odours. Correspondingly, an urban area will have its own characteristics and features that must be taken into account.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Anderson v. Jefferies</SOC><CITE>BCSC 1410</CITE><PARANUM>16</PARANUM></CASEREF>, RBOA, Tab 8.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>72. The character of the neighbourhood was determinative in this court's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Gallant v. Dugard</SOC></CASEREF>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Yates</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, RBOA, Tab 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> As here, the applicant in that case sought to have a boundary tree declared a nuisance so that he might remove it without the consent of his neighbour. He argued that the tree, a mature black walnut, caused a substantial interference by waking up him and his partner when nuts fell on the roof of his house. The court found that the applicant had failed to satisfy either branch of the test for nuisance. Justice Gray's comments on the relationship between the character of a particular locale and reasonableness of an interference are equally apposite in this case:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Gallant</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at paras. 25-26, RBOA, Tab 7.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>The applicant chose to purchase a house in a district of Oakville that is heavily populated by trees. The Town of Oakville and its residents take great pride in the Town's trees, and take steps to preserve them. The community as whole wishes to preserve the trees in this historic district.</P>
<P>It is not unreasonable, in my view, for the applicant to tolerate a degree of interference with this use and enjoyment of his property that is reflected in the evidence, having regard to the particular neighbourhood in which he resides, and having regard to the position of the Town and its residents with respect to the Town's trees in this historic district.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>73. The requirement that reasonableness be assessed having regard the identity of the parties and their neighbourhood is further basis to distinguish the <EM>Centrum</EM> decision, relied upon by the Applicants. The occupiers in that case were two commercial entities, the Institute of Chartered Accountants and Chez Moi Tavern Limited, and the properties were located in a commercial district on Bloor Street, in downtown Toronto.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Centrum</EM>, <EM>supra</EM>, at para. 1, ABOA, Tab 6.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Applicants' submission that <EM>Centrum</EM> is &ldquo;completely analogous&rdquo; ignores the fundamental difference in the nature of the parties and their respective interests, tolerances, and expectations in that case (in addition to the legislative distinction discussed above).</P>
<P>74. The Respondents are a passive actor in this case. They are not seeking to interfere or otherwise encroach upon[location omitted]&mdash;only to preserve one of the most beloved features of their home. A desire to maintain a status quo that is consonant with the character of a neighbourhood is not unreasonable. What is unreasonable is the Applicants' insistence that their desire to increase the value of their house for sale justifies the destruction of the Respondents' property.</P></BLOCK4></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P>75. The Respondents respectfully requests that this Application be dismissed, with costs.</P>
