<BLOCK1><TI>FACTUM OF THE APPLICANTS (Application returnable March 26, 2019)</TI>
<BLOCK2 LABEL="Part"><N>I</N><TI>OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. This is an application seeking an Order permitting the removal of a boundary tree located between the properties municipally known as [location omitted] [location omitted]and[location omitted]</P>
<P>2. The boundary tree is a nuisance. The Applicants, like many other home owners in the Moore Park area, wish to modernize their home and add an addition. The Applicants' design requires the removal of the tree. The City of Toronto has approved the Applicants' design and has issued the required building permits. The Committee of Adjustment for the City of Toronto approved the minor variances required for the Applicants' design to be implemented. Most importantly, the City of Toronto, Urban Forestry has issued a Tree Destruction Permit because in order to implement the Applicants' design Urban Forestry found &ldquo;that no reasonable alternatives to tree removal are possible and the tree qualifies for removal under the By-Law.&rdquo;</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI>APPLICANTS' RESPONDING SUBMISSIONS ON COSTS</TI>
<P>1. The Respondents were successful in resisting the Application brought by the Applicants and as such, are seeking a total of $77,091.35, inclusive of fees, disbursements, and HST, representing costs on a partial indemnity scale prior to February 14, 2019, due to the service of a <EM>Rule</EM> 49 Offer to Settle of the same date, and on a substantial indemnity scale thereafter. The Respondents alternatively seek to recover partial indemnity costs of $67,670.58. The Applicants' position is that a reasonable quantum of costs in these circumstances is $25,981.12, inclusive of fees, disbursements, and HST.</P>
<P>2. Pursuant to section 131 of the <EM>Courts of Justice Act</EM>, this Honourable Court has discretion with respect to costs awarded and may consider the factors listed under <EM>Rule</EM> 57.01 in exercising this discretion. In reviewing these factors, the Applicants submit that the costs sought by the Respondents in this matter are exorbitant in the circumstances.</P>
<P>3. One of the factors that the Court may consider is the amount of costs that an unsuccessful party could reasonably expect to pay in relation to the proceeding for which costs are being awarded. In doing so, the Court may compare the unsuccessful party's fees to those of the successful party<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Canadian National Railway v. Royal &amp; SunAlliance Insurance Co. of Canada</SOC><CITE>2005 CarswellOnt 4402</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. S.C.J.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (Ground J.) at paras 10-11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>. The Applicants attach their Bill of Costs, which list total fees on a partial indemnity scale of $17,982.00, exclusive of HST, that the Applicants would have handed up at the hearing. On a partial indemnity basis, the Applicants would have sought $22,505.24, inclusive of fees, disbursements, and HST. By comparison, the Respondents have claimed a total of $50,002.80 in partial indemnity fees, exclusive of HST. As such, there is a significant disparity between the costs incurred by each party and the costs sought by the Respondents are well beyond the reasonable expectations of the Applicants or any litigant in such a case.</P>
<P>4. This disparity is, in part, due to the increased rates charged by the Respondents' counsel. Senior counsel for the Respondents, Nader Hasan (&ldquo;Hasan&rdquo;), has been called to the bar for 12 years and charges an actual rate of $525.00/hour, whereas senior counsel for the Applicants, Christopher Cosgriffe (&ldquo;Cosgriffe&rdquo;) has 25 years of experience and is a Certified Specialist (Civil Litigation), and charges an actual rate of $500.00/hr.</P>
<P>5. The disparity in amounts claimed is also due to the number of hours expended by Respondents' counsel. For the sake of comparison, the Applicants also attach copies of their counsel's time entries, demonstrating a total of 86.6 hours incurred by Applicants' counsel with respect to the Application. Comparatively, the Respondents' counsel have docketed a total of 182.5 hours or about 100 hours more for the same application.</P>
<P>6. The Applicants submit that the fees to be awarded to the Respondents should be limited to those set out in the Applicants' Revised Bill of Costs, amounting to total fees of $21,058.00, exclusive of HST, which was if the Applicants were claiming on a substantial indemnity basis from February 14, 2019, resulting in a total of $25,981.12 inclusive of fees, disbursements, and HST.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Cross-Examinations</EM></TI>
<P>7. Three cross-examinations were conducted with respect to this Application. All took less than two hours and generated only 175 pages of transcripts. The Respondents have identified time spent with respect to preparation for and attendance at cross-examinations for both Hasan and Benjamin Kates (&ldquo;Kates&rdquo;). Kates and Cosgriffe attended all three cross-examinations and claimed 13.1 and 13.6 respectively on the bills of costs. Hasan attended only one of the cross-examinations and the Respondents have claimed a total of 15.3 hours for Hasan's time. It is unreasonable that the Respondents are claiming more hours for Hasan, who attended only one of the cross-examinations, than the hours worked for Kates and Cosgriffe.</P>
<P>8. Further, the hours claimed by both Hasan and Kates with respect to cross-examinations are duplicative. Due to the limited complexity of this matter, which related to the issue of nuisance caused by a boundary tree, it was not necessary for two counsel to participate in the cross-examinations in this matter.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Post-February 14, 2019</EM></TI>
<P>9. The Respondents have claimed a total of 86.3 hours for their counsel post-February 14, 2019 in the section of their Bill of Costs entitled &ldquo;Pleadings, Communications, Civil Practice Court&rdquo;. This time was incurred after the Respondents' Application Record was delivered on January 9, 2019. Time for cross-examinations is allocated under a separate &ldquo;Cross-Examination&rdquo; heading. It can be reasonably inferred that these 86.3 hours must then relate only to the preparation of the Respondents' Factum and Book of Authorities, and preparation for the hearing. Comparatively, counsel for the Applicants incurred only 37.1 hours for these same items, resulting in a significant difference of 49.2 hours.</P>
<P>10. In addition, the Respondents' claim for 86.3 hours post-February 14, 2019 is not only highly disproportionate to the hours for the Applicants' counsel, but is also disproportionate with respect to the average complexity of this matter. This Application saw three affidavits sworn, three cross-examinations that were each less than two hours, and twelve distinct cases put before the Court. Argument of the Application was for slightly more than half a day. The amount claimed by the Respondents is disproportionate to what needed to be done to have the Application heard.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI><EM>Summary</EM></TI>
<P>11. In light of the significant disparities between the hours incurred and rates charged by Respondents' and Applicants' counsel, the fees claimed by the Respondents are not appropriate. As a result, the Applicants submit that the fees awarded to the Respondents should be limited to $21,058.00, exclusive of HST, resulting in an award of no more than $25,981.12, inclusive of fees, disbursements, and HST.</P>
<P>April 24, 2019</P>
